Command was `(wget -q -O - http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/rss)'" "" (20849 20336 878317) obsolete 0 nil nil nil) ("Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk" "Latest news and features from guardian.co.uk, the world's leading liberal voice" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio" (20849 37943 480348) feed 0 nil nil ((title nil "Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio") (description nil "Latest news and features from guardian.co.uk, the world's leading liberal voice") (language nil "en-gb") (copyright nil "Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. 2013") (lastBuildDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 14:15:34 GMT") (docs nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds") (ttl nil "15") (image nil (title nil "Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk") (url nil "http://image.guardian.co.uk/sitecrumbs/Guardian.gif") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) (item nil (title nil "Is there too much historical fantasy on screen?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/da-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/97248?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ada-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy%3A1896371&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Historical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CFox+%28TV+network%29%2CGame+of+Thrones+%28TV+series%29%2CTelevision+industry+%28Media%29%2CUS+television+industry%2CMedia%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CUS+Elections%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sarah+Hughes&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+12%3A35&c8=1896371&c9=Article&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Da+Vinci%27s+Demons%3A+is+there+too+much+historical+fantasy+on+screen%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FHistorical+drama\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The eight-part drama starts tonight on Fox with Leonardo as a sword-wielding rogue. Later in the year sees a new version of The Three Musketeers, plus several pirate dramas and  other historical epics. Is it all too much swashbuckling and sorcery?</p><p>The problem with a show becoming a hit is that suddenly every one else wants a piece of the action. Thus, after <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/lost\" title=\"\">Lost</a>, we were inundated with overly complex dramas filled with secrets and cryptic clues (Flash Forward, The Event, Alcatraz); without <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/mad-men-tv-series\" title=\"\">Mad Men</a>'s Emmy success, it is unlikely networks would have been desperate to commission either Pan Am or The Playboy Club.&nbsp;And now,&nbsp;thanks to the success of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/game-of-thrones\" title=\"\">Game of Thrones</a>, viewers are being treated to a whole raft of historical fantasy shows.</p><p>Take <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2013/apr/16/da-vincis-demons-reinvents-leonardo\" title=\"\">Da Vinci's Demons</a>, which starts on Fox this evening. The eight-part drama recasts the renaissance artist Leonardo da Vinci as a charming rogue with an eye for the ladies, often seen flashing his chest while fending off assorted enemies. Or the new version of the Three Musketeers, coming to the BBC next year, starring Peter Capaldi as Cardinal Richelieu and Skins actor Luke Pasqualino as D'Artagnan. Sorcery and swordplay, it seems, will become even harder to escape from the schedules.</p><p>Elsewhere, US TV networks have two pirate dramas in the mix: Black Sails, a Treasure Island prequel in which, <a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/michael-bays-black-sails-trailer-441447\" title=\"\">judging by the eight-minute trailer</a>, Michael Bay indulges his twin desires to watch women kissing and blow things up a lot, and Crossbones, which stars John Malkovich as Blackbeard and is scripted by Luther's Neil Cross. Meanwhile, a big-budget version look at the life of Marco Polo produced by Harvey Weinstein is in the works at American cable channel Starz.</p><p>Over here, the BBC has clearly decided that the best way to imitate Game of Thrones's blend of backstabbing and betrayal is to strip away the fantasy trappings and head back to George R R Martin's original inspiration: the <a href=\"http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1496\" title=\"\">War of the Roses.</a></p><p>Later this year they will air <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yPBg9KK3gYo\" title=\"\">The White Queen</a>, a 10-part adaptation of Philippa Gregory's War of the Roses-set novel. That will be followed in 2014 by the much-anticipated BBC take on <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/hilary-mantel\" title=\"\">Hilary Mantel</a>'s Wolf Hall starring Mark Rylance as arch-conspirator Thomas Cromwell.</p><p>Yet, while it is easy to understand the rush to imitate the hugely successful Game of Thrones, do we really want to be subsumed in a sea of historical fantasy? As someone who owns a much-cherished box set of Sean Bean's Napoleonic war series <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5C8IuThoWuU\" title=\"\">Sharpe</a>, I'm always open to a certain amount of swashbuckling and bodice ripping. But even the biggest fan can worry that the bandwagon may be in danger of tipping.&nbsp;</p><p>With Da Vinci's Demons,&nbsp;it soon becomes clear that it's not quite as clever as Game of Thrones which is a great shame because in its better bits – the throwaway one-liners, the mischievous playing with history – Da Vinci's Demons feels a little like Sherlock or Merlin in tone (and it is no surprise to note that it is a BBC Worldwide co-production). It is a show that should work as&nbsp;great,&nbsp;blockbuster family entertainment but is instead trying too hard to be dark and edgy and adult.</p><p>But what do you think – will you be watching Da Vinci's Demons? Which of the other new shows would you watch? Can anyone replicate the success of Game of Thrones? And is there really room in your life for two pirate dramas? As ever let me know in the comments below …</p><p><em>Da Vinci's Demons starts on Fox tonight at 10pm.</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/fox\">Fox</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/game-of-thrones\">Game of Thrones</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/ustelevision\">US television industry</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/sarahhughes\">Sarah Hughes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Fox") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Game of Thrones") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "US television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 11:35:28 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/da-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy") (dc:creator nil "Sarah Hughes") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T11:35:28Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407507046") (media:keywords nil "Historical drama, Television, Drama, Fox, Game of Thrones, Television industry, US television industry, Media, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366370453802/Tom-Riley-as-Leonardo-Da--005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Greg Wiliiams/FOX") (media:description nil "Tom Riley as Leonardo Da Vinci in Da Vinci's Demons. Photograph: Greg Wiliiams/FOX")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366370461494/Tom-Riley-as-Leonardo-Da--010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Greg Wiliiams/FOX") (media:description nil "Tom Riley as Leonardo Da Vinci in Da Vinci's Demons. Photograph: Greg Wiliiams/FOX"))) (item nil (title nil "Last night's TV") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/brushing-up-on-british-tunnels") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/55738?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abrushing-up-on-british-tunnels%3A1896130&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CDanny+Baker%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sam+Wollaston&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1896130&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Brushing+Up+On+%E2%80%93+British+Tunnels%3B+Maureen+Lipman%3A+If+Memory+Serves+Me+Right%3B+Could+We+Survive+a+Mega-Tsunami%3F+%E2%80%93+TV+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">We're in a tunnel, being splurt-blasted by Danny Baker's words and wit and wisdom …</p><p>The most entertaining programme on TV last night? Easy: <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s1c4y\" title=\"Brushing Up On\"><strong>Brushing Up On&nbsp;–</strong></a> (BBC4). Brushing up on what? Tunnels, obviously: something, says presenter Danny Baker, all human beings are obsessed with. I'd like to have sat in on the meeting at which this one got commissioned (if that's how these things happen). So, Danny, you want to make a programme about tunnels? Like a documentary, but not really a documentary, because you're not finding anything out, or doing any reporting? And although there is a factual element to it, some of these facts have no basis in truth and are quite clearly plucked from your (over) vivid imagination? More like standup than documentary, then. Tunnel-based comedy, hmmm …</p><p>On the plus side, you don't need to go anywhere, apart from the BBC archive to dig out some old footage of tunnels and people tunneling, around which you can twist your tale. And toss in a few cheap graphics. It's only going to cost about a 140 quid to make, including your fee. You know what, let's do it!</p><p>I imagine that's how it went. In which case that commissioning editor is a bit of a hero, because the result is a little treat. The story of the Channel tunnel starts in 1802 with Napoleon, who was going to build an island (like Boris's) halfway across. It ends in 1990 with a man whose name (Graham) came out of the (hard) hat; he got to go through the hole to meet the Frenchman (Phillippe) who had been digging from the other side. In the 188 years in between, there's plenty of xenophobia; a man in a suit who trips up again and again; a comedy Frenchman saying \"bonjour\"; a machine that digs itself into a hole, dies, and then gets bought for £20,000 by a man named Ron; and&nbsp;more.</p><p>It's not just about the Channel tunnel, though. It's about hot Irish men, \"with iron in their arms and their buttocks\", building the London underground. It's about the tunnels under the Thames, and Swampy, and David Bellamy, and badgers, and a man named Don who watches the badgers.</p><p>It doesn't all work. At times it's hard even to know what Baker is on about. Some of it I think might actually be wrong (like the Dartford tunnel may have two lanes but these days they both head north, so, contrary to what DB says, the only way IS Essex). Who cares though, because so much of it is a joy. The word \"buttocks\" IS funny, as are men called Ron and Don; though not as funny as a man in a suit tripping over, on repeat; and the sentence: \"So you'd recommend fish-farming in a German war tunnel, then?\" from some old footage from the Channel Islands, is one of the greatest ever uttered.</p><p>It comes out so fast too. It's as if there's a fire hydrant on Baker's forehead, it's turned on full, connected to a high pressure hose and aimed at you, and you're being splurt-blasted by his words and wit and wisdom. No, maybe not wisdom. Imagination, then, and a lot of weird stuff, some of which is about tunnels. Fabulous. Bring on the bridges next week.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zvx\" title=\"Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right\"><strong>Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right</strong></a> (BBC1) was one of those documentaries that involves a non-expert celebrity going on a journey of discovery triggered partly by events in their own lives. You know the ones. So Maureen's finding out about memory, partly because her father lost his, and she's worried about hers. There's a bit of science, a bit of psychology, a bit of Paul McKenna, quite a lot of blah. She's amiable company, but the film is meandering, inconclusive, unmemorable.</p><p>And <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zqv\" title=\"Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?\"><strong>Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?</strong></a> (BBC2) was one of those what-if documentaries (thankfully, no lame drama element to this one: they're the worst). In fact, more of a what-when one, because this is going to happen. There's going to be a volcanic eruption and half of La Palma, one of the Canary islands, is going to slide into the sea. No great shame, you might think, but this will unleash a massive CGI wave three times the height of the Shard that will take out New York just like in The Day After Tomorrow, though less convincingly because this CGI wave doesn't have a Hollywood budget behind it.</p><p>They're screwed then, over there. What about us, though? Well, not great if you're in Penzance, I'm afraid. Brighton? Touch and go. But tucked away snuggly and smuggly round the corner here in London? I'll be fine, thank you.</p><p><a href=\"http://gu.com/p/3f8h9/tw via @guardian\" title=\" Watch this: TV highlights\">• Watch this: TV highlights</a></p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://tvlistings.guardian.co.uk/default.aspx\" title=\" Full TV listings\">• Full TV listings</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/danny-baker\">Danny Baker</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samwollaston\">Sam Wollaston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Danny Baker") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 06:00:13 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/brushing-up-on-british-tunnels") (dc:creator nil "Sam Wollaston") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T06:00:13Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407461768") (media:keywords nil "Television, Danny Baker, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306163825/Danny-Baker--005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guy Levy/BBC") (media:description nil "More standup than documentary ... Danny Baker's Brushing Up On - British Tunnels. Photograph: Guy Levy/BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306169471/Danny-Baker--010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guy Levy/BBC") (media:description nil "More standup than documentary ... Danny Baker's Brushing Up On - British Tunnels. Photograph: Guy Levy/BBC"))) (item nil (title nil "A week in radio: An Afghan story") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/everyday-story-of-afghan-folk") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/54708?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aeveryday-story-of-afghan-folk%3A1896020&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Afghanistan+%28News%29%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media&c6=Nosheen+Iqbal&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1896020&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Radio+review+%28G2+series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=An+Everyday+Story+of+Afghan+Folk%3B+Archive+on+4%3A+radio+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FAfghanistan\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">This play adapted from an Afghani soap opera would have been great in the 80s, but sounds a bit dull now<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\">An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00hg8dq\" title=\"Archive on 4\">Archive on 4</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/blogs/radiolab-blog/2013/apr/16/distance-of-moon/\" title=\"Radiolab\">Radiolab</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\"><strong>An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</strong></a> returned for a second series on Radio&nbsp;4 this week, filling in the daily 15 minute drama slot with an imagined take on village life on the Af-Pak border. \"Tell your father you want to marry Shireen, addict or not!\" yelled Meera Syal, playing the Pashtun wife of a poor farmer in her stock elderly Indian biddy accent, scolding a daughter with ideas above her station. The idea being education, the station being the school that pompous village leader Akbar Khan is secretly intent on blowing up.</p><p>This sort of thing would have been wonderful in the 80s – a worthy play adapted from an actual Afghani soap opera (<a href=\"http://www.pactradio.com/en/drama/news/bbc-radio-4-to-broadcast-a-season-of-the-pulay-poray-drama.php\" title=\"Pulay Poray\">Pulay Poray</a> in this case), boiling down the nuances of life and culture on the borderlands to two familiar dramatic tropes: arranged marriages and angry fathers. But it feels lazy and a bit dull in 2013. The mish-mash of accents delivered by the actors doesn't help, the lack of ambition even less so.</p><p>One radio show profiling another radio show should be too meta a concept to really work, but Judith Kampfner pulled it off for <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rv0m0/Archive_on_4_Radiolab/\" title=\"Archive on 4s look at Radiolab\"><strong>Archive on&nbsp;4's look at Radiolab</strong></a> last weekend, offering a solid primer on the cult US phenomenon broadcast on 300 American radio stations and downloaded as a podcast by 2 million listeners each week. What makes it so successful, asked Kampfner, and why are fellow broadcasters so in awe of it? Even Ira Glass, presenter of <a href=\"http://www.thisamericanlife.org/\" title=\"This American Life\"><strong>This American Life</strong></a>, was floored. \"They heard what we were doing and took the whole thing further,\" he cheerfully admitted. \"The aesthetic is much more evolved … it's more interactive, dynamic and fun.\" High praise.</p><p>Meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/\" title=\"Radiolab\"><strong>Radiolab</strong></a> skipped its usual format (esoteric science chat and brainy soundscapes) for a special reading by actor Liev Schrieber. What if the moon was just a jump away, asked hosts Jad Abumrad and Robert Krulwich. The answer was delivered in Italo Calvino's The Distance of the Moon, a trippy short story from the 60s, beautifully rendered in Schrieber's deep timbre.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/afghanistan\">Afghanistan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/nosheen-iqbal\">Nosheen Iqbal</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Afghanistan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 06:00:07 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/everyday-story-of-afghan-folk") (dc:creator nil "Nosheen Iqbal") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T06:00:07Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407452778") (media:keywords nil "Afghanistan, Radio, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366298613914/Meera-Syal-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Tristram Kenton/Tristram Kenton") (media:description nil "Meera Syal, star of An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk, as she appeared in Much Ado About Nothing for the RSC. Photograph: Tristram Kenton")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366298621995/Meera-Syal-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Tristram Kenton/Tristram Kenton") (media:description nil "Meera Syal, star of An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk, as she appeared in Much Ado About Nothing for the RSC. Photograph: Tristram Kenton"))) (item nil (title nil "Spartacus: box set review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/82184?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aspartacus-box-set-review%3A1895903&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Spartacus+%28TV+programme%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Phelim+O%27Neill&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+03%3A00&c8=1895903&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CReview&c13=Your+next+box+set+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Spartacus%3A+box+set+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FSpartacus\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">There's so much more to Spartacus than the sex, blood and gore – but nevertheless there is a great deal of sex, blood and gore ...</p><p>It's commonly thought that this <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ptX_pjz5s2k\" title=\"visceral, swaggering show\">visceral, swaggering show</a> fumbled its start, presenting opening episodes so full of sex and violence that many (mostly the sort of killjoys who find make-believe sex and violence automatically unpalatable) were unable to see anything else, or accept the context in which such strong elements were presented. Looking back on those introductory episodes now the show has finished on Sky 1, they are really not that different from what followed; Spartacus started with <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q94bZ0NyJEg\" title=\"everything turned up to 11\">everything turned up to 11</a> and never flagged. The always entertaining dialogue was as stylised as the action: \"You scale a mountain of ifs and I would add to its peak.\" It was up to you to get used to it; if you did, you'd be hooked on a show that constantly delivered the goods.</p><p>It also tragically lost its Spartacus when cancer took lead <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VtPfga7VitA\" title=\"Andy Whitfield\">Andy Whitfield</a>. While he was ill, after season one (Blood and Sand), a short prequel series (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ou2TvLK9jzg\" title=\"Gods of the Arena\">Gods of the Arena</a>) kept the show going and expanded the back-story of the many supporting characters, turning the show into more of an ensemble piece. John Hannah's furiously ambitious <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GW2sNb1cd-w\" title=\"Batiatus\">Batiatus</a>, Lucy Lawless as his equally <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUEj3mvrLbU\" title=\"ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennetts Crixus the undefeated Gaul\">ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennett's Crixus the undefeated Gaul</a>, Dustin Clare's swaggering gladiator <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s71sZrOlJHk\" title=\"Gannicus\">Gannicus</a>, Nick Tarabay's stupendously duplicitous <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AKMI2f1xkA0\" title=\"Ashur\">Ashur</a>: the show was full of memorable characters that it had no worries about killing off (it's no surprise that almost everyone dies, that's the kind of spoiler that is usually taught in schools).</p><p>When Whitfield's replacement, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJdh6yJBJpQ\" title=\"Liam McIntyre\">Liam McIntyre</a>, joined the show for series three, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tNdutDDCUQU\" title=\"Vengeance\">Vengeance</a>, and the final <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\" title=\"War of the Damned\">War of the Damned</a>, his Spartacus was suitably more sullen, less cocky, still as unrelentingly hateful of the Romans as before, but bearing the weight of a man who was fighting not just for revenge of his murdered wife, but for freedom for all. Knowing how it ends doesn't diminish its power; rather it comes loaded with a crushing inevitability. With no wasted episodes, Spartacus never drags its sandalled feet.</p><p>It turned out to be an extremely tightly plotted affair, the storytelling as flab-free as the athletic cast, full of twists, surprises, and such never-before-seen-on-TV things as a bridge made of corpses and a gay couple (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2J6p5lCFrA\" title=\"Agron and Nasir\">Agron and Nasir</a>, dubbed Nagron by fans) who make it to the end without anyone commenting on their sexuality. You get blood and gore but so much more.</p><p><br />Reading this on a mobile? <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\">Click here to view video</a></p><p>The levels of violence are insanely high; the screen is surreally sprayed with gore, and the fight choreography surpasses movie quality. But the violence is not used just to look cool – see, for instance, the episode Decimation, where we learn the proper use of the word, as 10% of a Roman squad are harrowingly beaten to death. It's inventive too: just when you think you've seen every combination of hacking and slashing a body apart, along comes the scene where Spartacus slices the entire front of someone's head off. That's variety for you.</p><p>While it wouldn't have been made were it not for the success of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol67qo3WhJk\" title=\"Gladiator\">Gladiator</a> and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDiUG52ZyHQ\" title=\"300\">300</a>, Spartacus ended up outclassing those high-grossing movies in almost every department, save popularity. The virtue of the long-form storytelling (39 episodes in all) is that even when a minor character dies it has the impact of losing, if not an old friend, then at least a long-term acquaintance. And the finale must be one of the most emotionally violent ever televised, with a message, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SYRGF0GWTD4\" title=\"delivered in Spartacuss pre-battle speech\">delivered in Spartacus's pre-battle speech</a>, that rings through the ages as he fights for those \"forced to toil and suffer while those in coin and position see their fortunes grow beyond need or purpose.\" 'Twas ever thus.</p><p>The Starz Channel's Spartacus is one of the TV highpoints of recent years – or at least it would be considered so, had it gathered more viewers. It may yet be regarded as such, for if there was ever a show that benefited from the boxset format, it's Spartacus. Watch a few episodes. If you don't like it then watch a couple more, because when it takes, you'll be gripped and put through the wringer.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/spartacus\">Spartacus</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/phelimoneill\">Phelim O'Neill</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Spartacus") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 14:00:02 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review") (dc:creator nil "Phelim O'Neill") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T23:06:13Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407442691") (media:keywords nil "Spartacus, Historical drama, Television, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290155216/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290161321/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC"))) (item nil (title nil "The return of The Fried Chicken Shop") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/33942?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areturn-of-fried-chicken-shop%3A1895793&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CFast+food+%28life+and+style%29%2CFood+and+drink++%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFood+and+Drink&c6=Stuart+Heritage&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+01%3A10&c8=1895793&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+return+of+The+Fried+Chicken+Shop&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The highly entertaining look at life in a London takeaway is coming back to Channel 4 for three new episodes. If they are as good as the first documentary, we are in for a treat</p><p>In February, Channel 4 aired <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-fried-chicken-shop-life-in-a-day\" title=\"\">The Fried Chicken Shop</a>, a one-off documentary set in a London fried chicken shop. Using the same fixed-rig setup that the channel loves to return to again and again, The Fried Chicken Shop took a week's worth of footage from Clapham's Roosters Spot eatery and distilled it into a tightly packed hour of entertainment. And it was much more fun than it had any right to be.</p><p></p><p>This week, Channel 4 announced that The Fried Chicken Shop is to return for three episodes that will repeat and expand on the premise of the original. We will still see the Roosters Spot staff grind out one impossibly long shift after another. We will still see Clapham's finest slumped over the counter at chucking-out time, manfully attempting to order a Mega Mix chicken burger with their last remaining molecule of dignity intact. But this time, we are promised, we will also get to follow some of the takeaway customers home. This new addition will almost certainly contain the most exciting footage of a lonely man sitting on a carpet in a bedsit and silently eating chips at 2am that British television has ever seen.</p><p></p><p>The beauty of The Fried Chicken Shop is its universality. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/24-hours-in-ae\" title=\"\">24 Hours in A&E</a> and feel admiration for the medical staff and their ability to maintain composure under extraordinary pressure. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-hotel\" title=\"\">The Hotel</a> and wonder why any of the guests agreed to let cameras into their rooms. But to watch The Fried Chicken Shop is to recognise a part of yourself.</p><p></p><p>Plenty of us, at one point or another, have bought fast food while drunk. Many of us will have done so without a second thought for the staff behind the counter. What The Fried Chicken Shop did so well was to make it clear how awful we probably are when we do this.  Judging by the show, the staff of Roosters Spot have put up with it all: aggressive drunks; attention-seeking drunks; people pretending to be disabled; drug dealers handing out business cards; and social media hipster dullards, who function as an argument for sawing a circle around the edge of London and letting it drop into the sea.</p><p></p><p>Watching the staff remain as good-natured and professional as they were in the face of such soul-sapping arsery was a joy. It was as heartwarming as anything else I have seen on television this year. And although it had the potential to lapse into the uncomfortably sneery classism that Channel 4's Gypsy programmes sometimes revel in, The Fried Chicken Shop staunchly refused to judge anyone. It didn't have a point to make, or an issue to force home, other than the awkward \"Wow, don't people eat a lot of chicken these days?\" message tacked on to the start. It was happy enough just to show us the chicken shop and let us reach our own conclusions. The first episode was magnificent. I can't wait to hang out there again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/fast-food\">Fast food</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink\">Food & drink</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stuart-heritage\">Stuart Heritage</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Documentary") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Factual TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Fast food") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Food & drink") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 12:10:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop") (dc:creator nil "Stuart Heritage") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T12:10:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407435148") (media:keywords nil "Television, Television & radio, Documentary, Factual TV, Fast food, Food & drink, Life and style") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284559725/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284566906/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes."))) (item nil (title nil "Why is EastEnders so bad?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/26566?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Awhy-is-eastenders-so-bad%3A1895696&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=EastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Television+Media%2CTV&c6=Homa+Khaleeli&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+11%3A27&c8=1895696&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Why+is+EastEnders+so+bad%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FEastEnders\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The soap's ratings have been sliding for more than a year – and a host of major characters have quit the square. What can it do to win back disgruntled fans?</p><p>There is a problem on the Square. Sure, there have been the usual tear-stained wedding dramas, squalling rows in the Queen Vic and near-incestuous couplings, but something is wrong: E20 has lost its edge. <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-facing-ratings-crisis-angry-1771100\" title=\"\">Ratings have been on the slide for more than a year</a>, while forums have been filling up with disgruntled fans. To put it like a Walford local: wossgaoinon?</p><p>Well, for a start, there are the recycled storylines. It's been a staggering 20 years since the angry baby that is Phil Mitchell first seduced his brother's breathy wife Sharon. Now, like a market-stall knockoff of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2310171/EastEnders-Phil-Mitchell-finally-gets-girl-Sharon-Rickman-succumbs-brutish-charms.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">they are at it again for a third time</a>. It's a plot so lacking in excitement that on Monday night, the cliffhanger ending was Sharon's six-year-old son (complete with Ann Widdecombe haircut) threatening to run away from home.</p><p>Stuck in a similarly boring rut are Max and Tanya, who have also been splitting up and getting back together on a loop since they first arrived in Walford, the London borough where marriages go to die. After several affairs, attempted murders and short-lived relationships with other people, Max has left Tanya once more – this time for Kirsty, whose larger-than-life lips, eyelashes and hair extensions have been stuck on in place of a personality. But inevitably Max is yet again pining after Tanya – a situation so predictable even the couple's children merely roll their eyes in response.</p><p>On top of this there are the non-plots – actual screen time was devoted to discovering who had stolen Dot's cold cuts from the fridge. And then there are the really unbelievable ones. Such as Masood, the square's nicest father figure, dating 19-year-old Ayesha, before the writers shamefacedly let it fizzle out. To cheer us up,  they've since put together attractive Denise and slimy egomaniac Ian Beale as the square's supposedly hilarious odd couple. But seeing as the soap operates a strict looks-blind policy to casting – with Phil Mitchell and Max as the square studs while Ray has been confined to the Fox sisters – it's hardly the most shocking of hookups.</p><p>Despite a cull of characters last year (I am still in mourning for the loss of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2248900/Nina-Wadia-quits-EastEnders-years-playing-Zainab-Masood.html\" title=\"\">Zainab Masood</a>), Eastenders still has some great ones – Kim is hilarious, Shirley does tough vulnerability brilliantly, and Kat and Alfie still have an impressive amount of chemistry. But instead of giving them some depth and storylines to progress with, there has been an emphasis on bringing back old favourites to bring back some sparks. When in truth, we don't want the same old faces but some new plotlines to put the drama back in to the doof doof endings.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/homa-khaleeli\">Homa Khaleeli</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "EastEnders") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Soap opera") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 10:27:19 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (dc:creator nil "Homa Khaleeli") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T11:18:56Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407427102") (media:keywords nil "EastEnders, Television, Drama, Soap opera") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279202222/EastEnders---third-time-l-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279210312/EastEnders---third-time-l-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron"))) (item nil (title nil "The Sea Devils: Doctor Who classic episode #5") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/the-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/24956?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode%3A1894855&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Doctor+Who+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CScience+fiction+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Dan+Martin&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+12%3A23&c8=1894855&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=The+best+Doctor+Who+episodes+of+all+time&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+Sea+Devils%3A+Doctor+Who+classic+episode+%235&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDoctor+Who\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Doctor is finally in colour, stranded on Earth – and up against his arch enemy, in the form of Roger Delgado's Master</p><h2>The Sea Devils: episode three (11 March 1972)</h2><p><em>The One Where …</em> Earth's original inhabitants rise from the sea, and the Master gets into The Clangers</p><p><em>SPOILER ALERT: We'll be discussing some of the Doctor Who adventures broadcast over the last 50 years. In this blog, we're looking at part three of The Sea Devils. It contains spoilers both about the specific episode and the story as a whole.</em></p><p>Two years earlier, the Silurians had proved a triumph, the story of a dormant pre-human race rising to reclaim the planet brought a spectrum of grey to Who. Unwilling to broker a deal to share the planet, the Brigadier had ordered their destruction. It was ripe for a sequel, and so producers decided to repurpose the story, this time with a marine setting. The Sea Devils doesn't quite have the bleak undercurrents of its predecessor but the scale and execution of this bring it out on top for me.</p><p>The co-operation of the navy meant the episode could live up to its blockbusting ambitions, and it's a a technical triumph packed with vintage moments: speedboats, swordfights, reversing-the-polarity-of-the-neutron flow and the Master watching The Clangers from his island prison. Oh yes, the Master; Roger Delgado is on electrifying form here.</p><p>This was at the height of the Doctor's Earth-bound adventures, as the Timelords exiled him to our world just as the show got colour. There was a lot of talk of The Bells of Saint John channelling James Bond a few weeks back, but Jon Pertwee's action-packed era was a closer cousin to 007 in the Roger Moore days. Unit – the military organisation for whom the Doctor is working as scientific advisor – doesn't feature here, but its buttoned-up British pomp is all over this navy-themed tale.</p><p>Of an impressive guest cast, most memorable is Martin Boddey as gluttonous minister Walker, ordering missile strikes in between mouthfuls of cake. The Sea Devils goes down as one of the most memorable Pertwee stories of all, and it's tricky to pick a best episode when the reach is so cinematic. So how about that cliffhanger to episode three, with that first monster emerging from the sea, surely one of the most memorable sequences in all of Who?</p><h2>Life aboard the Tardis </h2><p>The Timelords had exiled the Doctor to Earth, so there was no gallivanting round space and time in the third Doctor's early years. But there was a terrific ensemble in the Unit family, with a special favourite in Katy Manning as Jo Grant, one of the most beloved companions of all. Brought in to replace scientist Liz Shaw, whom producers had decided was a little too accomplished, Grant reversed the template of companions asking lots of questions. And she went round making an awful lot of tea without even being asked. But what the junior civilian operative for the UN lacked in progression, she more than made up for in fierce loyalty; the relationship between her and Pertwee's Doctor is one of the most tender in the show's history, and Katy Manning herself has gone on to be one of Who's proudest ambassadors. </p><h2>Behind the sofa </h2><p>The turtle-like\" sea devils\" (though never actually named as such) go down as a design classic, their menace only slightly undercut by the hospital fatigues they appear to be wearing. And that Silurian set-up, that someone was here before us is, as Steven Moffat noted in recent years, a \"movie franchise idea\". But The Sea Devils isn't in itself a scary story. And like the any Master story, the show is stolen by Roger Delgado's masterclass in polite psychopathy, returning after a year off. After being captured in The Daemons, he was imprisoned, and claiming to be reformed. But as the unfortunates at the prison soon discover, you can't keep a bad Timelord down; he's soon manipulating the governer and taking people down with his Jedi mind tricks.</p><h2>Behind the scenes </h2><p>The hovercraft sequence is also responsible for one of the fruitier production anecdotes. As Katy Manning recalls on the DVD extras, the vessel tipped over slightly to one side, leading to a \"nautical rugby scrum\". As she said with a cackle: \"It was a pretty exciting moment actually. I had something like 24 sailors on top of me, now there's a memory! I said to them afterwards: 'I'm going to have to marry all of you; we've just been too close,' and Jon was actually deeply concerned, he was not happy about that moment.\" (The production proved even more challenging for Delgado, who couldn't swim.)</p><h2>Fragments</h2><p>• \"Reverse the polarity of the neutron flow\", might be the third Doctor's most famous catchphrase, but he actually only ever used it twice: here, and in his anniversary comeback in The Five Doctors.</p><p>• I tweeted Manning at the weekend to tell her I was watching her in The Sea Devils. She replied:</p><p>I'm not quite sure what that means.</p><p>• Another iconic sequence here is the sight of what is quite clearly a burly stunt guy's bottom standing in for Manning. The man in question was named Stuart Fell.</p><p>• The Doctor, we learn, was a close personal friend of Horatio Nelson.</p><p>• Would they really have kept fencing swords right next to the prison cell of a dangerous criminal?</p><h2>Further reading </h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/seadevils/detail.shtml\" title=\"\">The official BBC page, with the usual list of amusing goofs.</a></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.radiotimes.com/blog/2009-12-14/doctor-who-the-sea-devils\" title=\"\">A Radio Times re-appraisal from a few years ago</a>.</p><p>• <a href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20080629134959/http://www.gallifreyone.com/review.php?id=3l\" title=\"\">And here's a review from those sensible people at Outpost Gallifrey</a></p><h2>Next time </h2><p>The one with the Maggots! Yes, we really are doing The Green Death, after the wrong listing last time. Sorry about that.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/doctor-who\">Doctor Who</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/science-fiction\">Science fiction</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/danmartin\">Dan Martin</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Doctor Who") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Science fiction") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 11:23:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/the-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode") (dc:creator nil "Dan Martin") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T11:30:17Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407309642") (media:keywords nil "Doctor Who, Science fiction, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/online/2013/4/17/1366191009306/The-Sea-Devils-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC") (media:description nil "The Sea Devils Photograph: BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/online/2013/4/17/1366191015018/The-Sea-Devils-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC") (media:description nil "The Doctor and a 'sea devil'. Photograph: BBC"))) (item nil (title nil "Marc Maron: podcast turned TV star") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/marc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/45669?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amarc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv%3A1894826&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Comedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CPodcasting+%28Media%29%2CInternet%2CDigital+media%2CMedia%2CComedy+live+%28Stage%29%2CCulture&c5=Digital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTechnology+Gadgets%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Diane+Shipley&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+05%3A42&c8=1894826&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Marc+Maron+is+the+latest+comedy+star+to+go+from+podcast+to+TV+pilot&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FComedy\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The route from internet audio show to TV and publishing success is well trodden in the US, but why are so few British comics keen to follow suit?</p><p>Last week IFC (the network that produces Portlandia) released the trailer for <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OqVaAqOIpYA\" title=\"\">Maron</a>, comedian Marc Maron's semi-autobiographical sitcom, which premieres in May. Its creator/star also has a book of essays, called Attempting Normal, published at the end of this month. But just four years ago, by his own admission, Maron <a href=\"http://www.believermag.com/exclusives/? read=\"interview_maron\"\" title=\"\">\"had nothing going on\"</a>. Having made his name in the 90s alternative comedy scene, he had lost touch with his more famous peers, including Louis CK and Patton Oswalt. Twice-divorced and fired from his third radio hosting gig in four years, Maron moved from New York to LA with three cats and few prospects. The 49-year-old's current career revival is all thanks to his hugely popular podcast, WTF, a twice-weekly interview show where he has swapped laughs and neuroses with everyone from Sarah Silverman to Robin Williams.</p><p>Now he's following in the footsteps of Scott Aukerman, whose improv podcast Comedy Bang! Bang! was also adapted for television by IFC, and Chris Hardwick, creator of The Nerdist podcast. Not content with one TV show, Hardwick also fronts a post-Walking Dead discussion called Talking Dead, has filmed a pilot for Comedy Central and last month launched the first series of the Nerdist TV show for BBC America. While he gained notoriety presenting cheesy dating shows in the 90s, it took a podcast to give him credibility. And he's not the only one.</p><p>Aisha Tyler is probably best known for playing Ross's girlfriend Charlie on Friends, but her Girl on Guy podcast made a wider audience aware of her comedy roots. As a result, she was announced as the new host of Whose Line Is It Anyway? last month and <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Self-Inflicted-Wounds-Heartwarming-Tales-Humiliation/dp/0062223771/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1365974995&sr=8-1&keywords=self+inflicted+wounds\" title=\"\">has her own book coming out this summer</a>. Meanwhile, comedian Pete Holmes has parlayed the success of his podcast You Made It Weird into <a href=\"http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/02/26/pete-holmes-conan-obrien-late-night-show-tbs/\" title=\"\">an upcoming sketch show</a>. And although it wasn't true, <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-nbc-renews-carson-daly-alec-baldwin-rumors-20130410,0,453985.story\" title=\"\">a recent rumour</a> that 30 Rock actor Alec Baldwin would take over Carson Daly's late-night talkshow seemed plausible thanks to the interviewing prowess he has shown on his own podcast, <a href=\"http://www.wnyc.org/shows/heresthething/\" title=\"\">Here's the Thing</a>.</p><p>When podcasts started back in 2004, few people realised their career-boosting potential. Pioneers such as Jesse Thorn and Dan Klass made quality shows that attracted loyal audiences and media coverage. But when I fired up my first MP3 player in 2005, I listened to a lot of podcasts that featured unintended sound effects and prolonged drunken giggling fits. Their creators often described them as \"homemade radio shows\" and that was exactly how they sounded.</p><p>They have become considerably slicker since then. To be a comedian in the US without a podcast is increasingly to be an oddity. It may even be a liability. Podcasts are a becoming an easy way for TV networks to find fresh talent with an established following. The potential for them to be used as a springboard to writing, acting, and presenting jobs is huge.</p><p>But they haven't taken off in quite the same way in the UK. Here podcasts tend to be drawn from popular radio shows made by established media corporations (such as <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-danny-baker-show/id330285088\">Danny Baker's BBC podcast</a>) rather than original, independently produced content. One exception is The Ricky Gervais Show, which Channel 4 adapted into an animated series in 2010. But Gervais had established a career in entertainment long before he hit \"record\".</p><p>So why are up-and-coming comedians in the UK less interested in building a millions-strong audio audience than their US counterparts? Perhaps because we have a more thriving live scene – America has no real equivalent to the Edinburgh festival, and the comparative size of our countries means it's far easier for British comedians to build a following by touring. Or it may just be that we're a step behind. Either way, it's a shame.</p><p>Cheaper and easier to put together than a YouTube production (and marginally less likely to attract incendiary comments), podcasts can provide a low-risk, low-cost way to try out new material, and not just for comedians. Releasing chapters of his audiobooks as podcasts helped <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/01/books/01podb.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0\" title=\"\">Scott Sigler become a self-publishing superstar</a>. Perhaps it's time for writers and performers on this side of the Atlantic to take note – and pick up a mic.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/podcasting\">Podcasting</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/internet\">Internet</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/digital-media\">Digital media</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dianeshipley\">Diane Shipley</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "US television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Podcasting") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Internet") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Digital media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Tue, 16 Apr 2013 16:42:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/marc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv") (dc:creator nil "Diane Shipley") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-16T17:39:09Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407307182") (media:keywords nil "Comedy, Television & radio, US television, Comedy, Television, Podcasting, Internet, Digital media, Media, Comedy, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366128783236/Marc-Maron-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Cassie Wright/WireImage") (media:description nil "Marc Maron's semi-autobiographical sitcom Maron premieres in May. Photograph: Cassie Wright/WireImage"))) (item nil (title nil "Mad Men: season six, episode three") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/mad-men-season-six-episode-three") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/64839?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amad-men-season-six-episode-three%3A1895537&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Mad+Men+%28TV%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Paul+MacInnes&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+11%3A00&c8=1895537&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=Notes+from+the+break+room+%28Mad+Men%29&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Mad+Men%3A+season+six%2C+episode+three&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FMad+Men\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">In which Pete Campbell's marriage falls apart, we find out what beans mean and peek through a brothel wall at Don's younger self</p><p><em>SPOILER ALERT: This blog is for those who are watching season six of Mad Men. Don't read on if you haven't seen episodes one and two</em></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/11/mad-men-season-six-episode-one-two\" title=\"\"><em>Catch up with Paul MacInnes's episode one and two blog here </em></a></p><p><strong>Episode three: The Collaborators</strong></p><h2>'It's just filled with profanity, marijuana smoking and simulated sexual acts … Oh, and a few songs' – Pete Campbell<br /></h2><p>The reign of Pete Campbell as the most unpleasant lothario in Cos Cob did not last long and neither was it edifying to watch. Determined to indulge himself as retribution for being made to live in the suburbs, Pete's first conquest was driven deeper into mental illness and his second ended up the victim of domestic violence. The ultimate consequence of this appears to be the immediate end of Pete's marriage. So at least something good came out of it.</p><p>Pete always seemed an unlikely type to inspire uncontrollable desire in women. His narrow-set features have something of the rodent about them, or perhaps a stoat. He's weedy and pale and seems shorn of any sense of romance (the spartan decor of his shag pad for, example, makes it look like something closer to a dungeon). This by the way, is without even touching upon the subject of his character which, when all's said and done, hardly works in his favour either.</p><p>Yet at the very beginning of this episode we get the distinct sense that Pete has beguiled not one but two neighbourhood women, while their husbands are stood in the next room. Those men, it has to be said, are in turn quite crassly chatting up Trudy Campbell. The conclusion one is reluctantly expected to draw from this juxtaposition is that Pete, by comparison, is a sophisticate. Topped off with his references to Hair, it seems the guy's a regular bohemian too.</p><p>So maybe Pete is simply taking advantage of a suburban desire for frisson. Or perhaps his neighbour, Brenda, just wanted access to a bolthole each time she came to Manhattan to shop. Either way, the next we see of her she's dressed like Jackie O and entirely willing to succumb to Pete's plodding advances.</p><p>Just a few days later, Brenda spills into the Campbells' sitting room, her nose bloodily busted and her husband's howl of \"You're Campbell's problem now\" trailing immediately behind. Pete plays the situation much as you'd expect: short of sympathy on the one hand and with cunning on the other. He suggests Brenda make her own way to a hotel in the middle of the night, before suddenly offering a lift when he realises his wife might drive her instead and find out the truth along the way.</p><p>That the truth does come out means the final scene in the Campbell household ends with Pete being instructed as to the scope of his micturatory privileges (he's not allowed to open his flies within 50 miles of his home). When she tells Pete she has decided to end their marriage, Trudy reveals a lot that we have really not seen before. She has proven cannier than we are often led to believe; she knew exactly what Pete's pad was intended for. She is also stern, clear and deliberate – less the subservient partner, more the daughter of a Vicks Chemical executive. Pete leaves the family home and dosses down in his office. </p><p>****</p><p>Away from the suburbs and back to the big city, where everyone's scrapping over condiments. There's an air of the ridiculous about proceedings, with people speaking in hushed tones of how \"beans brought in ketchup\" and asking themselves \"what can we do for ketchup?\" The reality for both <a href=\"http://madmen.wikia.com/wiki/Sterling_Cooper_Draper_Pryce\" title=\"\">SCDP</a> and <a href=\"http://madmen.wikia.com/wiki/Cutler_Gleason_and_Chaough\" title=\"\">Cutler, Gleason, and Chaough</a> is more serious, though, as Ken watches his ambitious plans being stifled and Ted Chaough plans to take advantage of a loose set of lips.</p><p>Ken's plan was simple: get beans to bring in ketchup and then, despite the expressed wishes of beans, run away with ketchup, the Coca-Cola of condiments. It was a simple plan and one entirely in keeping with the unsentimental nature of his business, but it was scotched by Don. Don felt that beans were owed some loyalty, that \"sometimes you gotta dance with the one that brung ya\". That hokey justification was entirely sentimental and entirely inconsistent with Don's subsequent, brilliant undermining of hideous Herb from Jaguar. Herb had brought Jaguar to SCDP and wanted them to change their strategy for his benefit and pitch it to his bosses too. Don did just as he was asked, but did it so egregiously that Herb's higher-ups refused to take the advice. An act of solidarity with Joan guided Don's actions, a personal act that may yet undermine his business interests.</p><p>There's nothing personal in the way that Ted leaps all over the news that Heinz ketchup might be up for grabs. Well there is, I guess, in that Ted sees SCDP as \"the enemy\". There's certainly no sentiment though as Peggy's accidental revelation of her late-night conversation with Stan, leads to the preparation of a brief the very next morning. Betraying information is how wars are won, Ted tells Peggy. \"He underestimated you.\"</p><p>****</p><p>Flashbacks are back back back. We know that Dick Whitman came from the school of hard knocks and, also, from the school of knocking shop. Here we get to see his time in the whorehouse. We are introduced to Ernestine the madam and Mack the rooster and Charlotte the prostitute in a scene that's eerily down home, all full of pleasantries and sweet swing music in the background. Later the tone changes starkly enough as Dick watches Mack having sex with his pregnant stepmother through a keyhole.</p><p>An elegant segue follows this scene as the camera pans past a sullen Dick, through the whorehouse wall, and out into the corridor of Don's apartment block. Don is there, shuffling towards his front door having allowed his priapism to take him to the verge of a disastrous encounter with Sylvia Rosen. He's just a gigolo, the old time song tells us, whose youth will pass away. (And what will they say of him then?) That Don's sex drive comes partly from a compulsion to demean his better self becomes clearer as time goes on.</p><p>****</p><p>As yet, Megan Draper has not a clue about her husband's infidelity and neither does she know he feels the pair are \"drifting apart\". She is, however, experiencing traumas of her own. An unplanned pregnancy in Hawaii is followed by a miscarriage and not only is Megan unable to share this event with anyone, it confirms in her another secret; her unwillingness to have children at all.</p><p>This is all worked out through a spontaneous confession to Sylvia in the washroom and, later, a dishonest conversation with Don. On both occasions, Megan's pain is coloured by her self-involvement. She assumes a sympathetic hearing from Sylvia, only to find that a shared Catholic upbringing resulted in very different moral codes. With Don, meanwhile, she jumps on an open-ended offer to have a conversation about children \"whenever you want\", to avoid the question altogether.</p><p>Don raises his eyebrows at this and we see that his willingness to accept Megan's indulgence of her own interests is limited. We also know, however, that Don is a hypocrite. He may think his desire to start another family is the normal, responsible thing, but he also feels free to ignore familial responsibilities. There is a generational difference between this couple, but they share a common selfishness.</p><h2>Notes</h2><p>We're only at episode three but already Bob Benson is making inroads. He's earned the trust of Pete, who allowed him to buy the most intimate of products for him. He's worked his obsequy on Herb with enough success to be granted the role of office tour guide. What next? A blowback from Stan?</p><p>We've not seen enough of Joan Holloway so far this season but she has been afforded one zinger of a line. In response to Herb's nauseating insistence that \"I know there's a part of you that wants to see me,\" she replies: \"I know there's a part of you that you haven't seen in years.\"</p><h2>Time stamps</h2><p>The <a href=\"http://www.clemson.edu/caah/history/FacultyPages/EdMoise/viet8.html\">Tet offensive</a> was one of the most notorious events in the Vietnam war, as the Viet Cong took advantage of a ceasefire (for the Vietnamese new year) to unleash brutal assaults on several south Vietnamese cities. These assaults were, in turn, crushed equally brutally by US and South Vietnamese forces. When this news is announced during this episode, Don and Sylvia pay no attention, too busy discussing the etiquette of dinner between adulterous couples.</p><p>The greatest conspiracy theory of the 20th century – who killed Kennedy? – was about to get a leg up as a Louisiana district attorney Jim Garrison <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Shl-F5qHN4U\">revealed to the American public</a> his belief that Lee Harvey Oswald had not acted alone.</p><h2>Culture club</h2><p>Hair: The American Tribal Love Rock Musical, to give it its full name, made its debut off-Broadway in 1967. It transferred to Broadway in the spring of 68 and slightly revised its bonkers premise for a broader audience. One of the changes involved turning the character of Claude from a space alien to a human. Its subsequent success may have lain partly in such revisions, but also in the fact it wasn't nearly as <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/theatre/2009/04/13/090413crth_theatre_als\">counter-cultural</a> as it thought it was.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/mad-men-tv-series\">Mad Men</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/paulmacinnes\">Paul MacInnes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Mad Men") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "US television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 22:00:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/mad-men-season-six-episode-three") (dc:creator nil "Paul MacInnes") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T08:34:17Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407393342") (media:keywords nil "Mad Men, Drama, Historical drama, US television, Television, Television & radio") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Columnists/Columnists/2013/4/17/1366219966907/Peggy-Olsen-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "internet") (media:description nil "Peggy Olsen in season 6, episode 3 of Mad Men, The Collaborators. Photograph: internet")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Columnists/Columnists/2013/4/17/1366219972881/Peggy-Olsen-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "internet") (media:description nil "Peggy Olsen in season 6, episode 3 of Mad Men, The Collaborators."))) (item nil (title nil "The genius of Davina McCall") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/five-minutes-to-fortune-davina-mccall") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91008?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Afive-minutes-to-fortune-davina-mccall%3A1894496&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Game+shows+%28TV+genre%29%2CDaytime+TV%2CEntertainment+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Stuart+Heritage&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+01%3A25&c8=1894496&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Five+Minutes+to+a+Fortune%3A+the+genius+of+Davina+McCall&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FGame+shows\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Channel 4's new gameshow would just be more daytime wallpaper in the hands of your average host. But Davina makes the daftest ideas watchable</p><p>Any idiot can present a daytime television gameshow. Just look at the schedules for proof. On any given day this week, the bored and housebound are asked to endure gameshows presented by estate agents (Phil Spencer's The Common Denominator), DIY men (Nick Knowles's Perfection), retired PR types (Nick Hewer's Countdown), newsreaders (Dermot Murnaghan's Eggheads) permanently corpsing comedians (Bradley Walsh's The Chase) and genuinely objectionable, insanely dressed egomaniacs (Deal or No Deal).</p><p>But while it's true that any idiot can present a daytime gameshow, it takes someone special to make a daytime gameshow that's actually worth watching. It's for this reason that I have become slightly addicted to Davina McCall's new show <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/five-minutes-to-a-fortune\" title=\"\">Five Minutes to a Fortune</a>.</p><p>Five Minutes to a Fortune should be terrible. Because it's a daytime gameshow – and daytime gameshows are only commissioned if they come with a set of rules so impenetrably convoluted that they may as well be written in Chicomuceltec – I won't explain exactly how it works here. The key thing to know is that there's a giant egg timer filled with 50,000 £1 coins that drain away as a contestant answers questions. If they answer the questions quickly, they keep the money. If they're slow, the egg timer sprays a fat sneeze of coins out into oblivion after every round, diminishing the total prize.</p><p>At first, the whole thing comes off as a pointlessly opportunistic poor cousin of <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-million-pound-drop-live\" title=\"\">Million Pound Drop</a>. \"Hey,\" you can see some high-ranking Channel 4 department head shouting in a boardroom, a torn-off ratings printout clutched to their chest. \"The kids love TV shows about Davina McCall watching money fall through stuff! She's the queen of watching money falling through stuff! Someone invent me another show for Davina to present. But – and I have to make this as clear as I possibly can – money has to fall through stuff. It has to.\" Hopefully if Five Minutes to a Fortune becomes as successful as Million Pound Drop, we'll get another show featuring McCall watching money fall through stuff. Maybe one where contestants have to dig postal orders out of a gutter with a coat hanger. It'll be brilliant.</p><p>Anyway, despite all this – and despite other wobbly factors, like the show's infinitely stupid \"STOP THE DRAIN!\" catchphrase – Five Minutes to a Fortune is an endlessly enjoyable television programme. And much of that, it has to be said, is down to the McCall. Davina is famously Good With People. She took Streetmate's creepy premise and made it warm and enjoyable. She single-handedly held Big Brother together by being empathetic and understanding instead of, say, obliviously shrieking platitudes at housemates such as Brian Dowling did during his thankfully curtailed tenure as host.</p><p>And now she's the secret weapon in Five Minutes to a Fortune too. Most people, if they ever found themselves in Davina's position, would become so completely worn down by the thought of having to repeat the show's needlessly complicated rules to a procession of actual morons again and again that they'd eventually snap and take a blind swing at a contestant's head. Not Davina, though. She's the picture of grace throughout. Even when, as with yesterday's episode, she has to spend what seems like a full calendar year trying to communicate the names of former Doctor Who actors to a struggling nitwit via a series of increasingly strangulated mimes and yelps.</p><p>If a gameshow lives or dies by its host, then McCall has ensured that Five Minutes to a Fortune will last a very long time indeed. Long enough for people to fully understand all of the show's rules? Maybe. That's how much fun it is.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/game-shows\">Game shows</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/daytime-tv\">Daytime TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/entertainment\">Entertainment</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stuart-heritage\">Stuart Heritage</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Game shows") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Daytime TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Entertainment") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Tue, 16 Apr 2013 12:25:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/five-minutes-to-fortune-davina-mccall") (dc:creator nil "Stuart Heritage") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-16T12:30:37Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407270582") (media:keywords nil "Game shows, Daytime TV, Entertainment, Television & radio, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366113755675/Davina-McCall-in-Five-Min-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Channel 4") (media:description nil "Davina McCall in Five Minutes To a Fortune   Photograph: Channel 4")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366113763608/Davina-McCall-in-Five-Min-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Channel 4") (media:description nil "Davina McCall in Five Minutes To a Fortune   Photograph: Channel 4"))) (item nil (title nil "Martin and Gary Kemp: 'We complement each other'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/19/martin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/3986?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amartin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet%3A1894802&ch=Life+and+style&c3=Guardian&c4=Family+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CMusic%2CPop+and+rock+%28Music+genre%29%2CCulture%2CFilm%2CEastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Pop+Music%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFamily+and+Relationships%2CTV&c6=Nick+Duerden&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A00&c8=1894802&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Martin+and+Gary+Kemp%3A+%27We+complement+each+other%27&c66=Life+and+style&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FLife+and+style%2FLife+and+style%2FFamily\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">They went from being new romantics in Spandau Ballet to playing London gangsters in the film The Krays. Now the brothers are about to appear on TV together again</p><p>An enduring tale of sibling harmony, Gary and Martin Kemp have spent decades working companionably alongside one another without ever, publicly at least, succumbing to fraternal combustion. The arts, and particularly pop music, is&nbsp;littered with brothers (more so, curiously, than sisters) who have tried to do the same and failed, among them Ray and Dave Davies of the Kinks and Noel and Liam Gallagher of Oasis, each undone by ego and the need to dominate. But the Kemps are different, an anomaly. Now&nbsp;both in their 50s, they remain essentially one and the same, and consequently stronger together than the sum of their parts.</p><p>But how? Gary Kemp, who, at 53, is two years Martin's senior, thinks that it is down to their upbringing. \"There were only four of us in our family: my mum, my dad, me, him. They were devoted to us, and we were devoted to&nbsp;them. It was them that gave us our sense of responsibility to one another, our moral compass. We've never lost it.\"</p><p>Initially, they were both child actors, often being cast alongside one another. Then, in the late 70s, they formed Spandau Ballet, new romantic goliaths with an unusual sense of fashion and a gift for mainstream balladry. The band ultimately split acrimoniously, but the Kemp brothers' partnership remained intact and, in 1990, they revived their first love, acting, playing Reg and Ronnie Kray in The Krays. They have dabbled in music and acting ever since, sometimes apart, more frequently in&nbsp;tandem.</p><p>This month, they return to the small screen, fronting the documentary Gangs of Britain, in which they explore British gang culture past and present. As ever, they make a good team, but do they never get sick of working with each other? Do they not crave a little autonomy?</p><p>Gary smiles. \"Not really, no, because we get on, we complement each other. Also, we're different people, with different personalities. What Martin does, I would never attempt, and vice versa, I think.\"</p><p>Is this true? To the viewing public at least, this is less clear. Surely casting directors could request either of them?</p><p>Gary remains insistent. \"No really, we are completely different. I'm more hyper, he is more laidback. I'm a control freak, I've always lusted for cultural things. Martin is more physical, more charismatic.\"</p><p>\"Charisma always was the important thing to me,\" Martin says. \"I joined Spandau Ballet not because I wanted to be the best musician in the world, but because I wanted to be Elvis Presley, Marlon Brando.\"</p><p>\"Sexual attraction,\" Gary suggests.</p><p>Martin chuckles. \"Yes,\" he says. \"I&nbsp;wanted that.\"</p><p>When I meet the Kemps in their PR offices, both look immaculate: suited and booted, hair swept back, their jawlines, up close, improbably strong. Gary is, indeed, the more hyper, the more effusive, while Martin has clearly learned plenty from watching Brando. Sitting in a large armchair that seems too small for him, and interlocking his fingers, he doesn't say much, but instead broods with a quiet intensity.</p><p>They were born and brought up in Islington, north London. Their father was a printer, their mother a seamstress, and they were latchkey children who joined a drama club for want of anything better to do after school. But in the 60s, the local Anna Scher children's theatre drama club was to British television what the Brit School is to today's pop charts: a conveyor belt of readymade talent. They were soon appearing in children's TV programmes and small films. At 16, Gary, a Bowie obsessive, started a band, and when they required a new bassist, he asked Martin not because Martin had any musical prowess – he hadn't – but because \"he was the coolest guy we knew, always popular with the girls. If anyone was going to get us magazine front covers, it was him.\"</p><p>Alongside Duran Duran, Spandau Ballet dominated the early 80s with their flash swagger, but success was tempered by boiling backroom rivalries. \"Me and Martin would fight occasionally, sure,\" Gary says, \"but no&nbsp;one could ever take sides because it&nbsp;would blow over in no time. If I argued with Tony [Hadley, the lead singer], on the other hand, it would be a disaster. It could have gone on for weeks – for ever.\"</p><p>\"It did,\" says Martin, laughing.</p><p>Band harmony ruptured, seemingly irrevocably, in the late 80s, but when the band finally split in 1990, the Kemps landed on their feet. That same&nbsp;year, the film The Krays established their acting careers, though neither achieved as much big-screen success in its wake as they had hoped. In the mid-90s, Gary decamped to Los Angeles to give Hollywood a go. Martin soon followed. \"We were going up for the same auditions a lot of the time, obviously,\" Martin says, \"but we understood that; there was no getting around it.\"</p><p>Nevertheless, they did try, by having separate agents. \"But,\" says Gary, \"sometimes Martin would get a script I&nbsp;hadn't been sent, and it was difficult not to phone my agent and say, 'Hey, he's got it, why haven't I?'\"</p><p></p><p>Both returned to the UK, and in 1998 Martin landed a major role in EastEnders. I ask how Gary felt about this and he tells me I'm forgetting something. Three years earlier, Martin had been diagnosed with a brain tumour – two, in fact. \"It was a terrible time. I felt awful for him, and so guilty. I was the older brother, and here he was with this terrible disease, not me. So when he got better and landed EastEnders, all I felt was pride and relief.\"</p><p>\"That was the main reason I took the part,\" Martin says. \"I'd had three years of illness. I needed to change that, to leave that part of my life behind.\"</p><p>In January 2009, illness tested them again when they lost both parents within four days of one another. \"An absolute disaster,\" Gary says. Their mother had been sick, and was in hospital for a heart operation. The family visited her one day, but by the time they got home, their father was behaving strangely. Complaining of a whooshing in his ear, he said he needed the toilet. \"He was in there a long time. I called out to him, and he said: 'I'm all right, boy.' But his voice sounded strange.\"</p><p>He had had a massive heart attack. Moments later, Gary was in the bathroom giving his father the kiss of life. He died a few days later. Telling their mother was the hardest thing he has ever had to do. \"She simply didn't want to live. She gave up.\"</p><p>But in this decision, he says, there was a kind of solace, peace, even. \"Our parents had never spent a day apart. They were so devoted, so old-fashioned, really. With him gone, she was lost. She looked around her and said: 'All is fine.' What she meant was, my wife was about to have a baby, Spandau were getting back together again after 19 years, and she was confident that both me and Martin were happy. So she was right, everything was fine, and she could go. Two days later, she was gone. We had a joint funeral.\"</p><p>Today, Gary lives in central London with his second wife. He has four sons. Martin and his wife live in Herefordshire with one daughter and one son. Their families socialise a lot, and the brothers will continue to work together. They would like to do more documentaries, and are in discussion to co-direct a film. The union has been fruitful so far, why stop now?</p><p>\"Mum and Dad were fantastic parents, and they instilled a lot of pride in us, a lot of love,\" says Gary. Martin nods solemnly. \"We've taken a lot from them, I think,\" he says. \"Me and Gary, the way we are – it's all down to them.\"</p><p></p><p><em>• </em><a href=\"http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/shows/gangs-of-britain.html\" title=\"\"><em>Gangs of Britain</em></a><em> begins on the Crime & Investigation Network, Sky Channel 553 at 9pm on 21 April</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/family\">Family</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/popandrock\">Pop and rock</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/nick-duerden\">Nick Duerden</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Family") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/music")) "Music") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/music")) "Pop and rock") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Film") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "EastEnders") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Soap opera") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Interviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 14:00:04 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/19/martin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet") (dc:creator nil "Nick Duerden") (dc:subject nil "Life and style") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T14:00:04Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407303498") (media:keywords nil "Family, Life and style, Music, Pop and rock, Culture, Film, EastEnders, Television, Drama, Soap opera") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366127459354/Martin-and-Gary-Kemp.-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Linda Nylind/Guardian") (media:description nil "Martin (left) and Gary Kemp: 'Our parents gave us our sense of responsibility to one another, our moral compass.' Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366127466579/Martin-and-Gary-Kemp.-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Linda Nylind/Guardian") (media:description nil "Martin, left, and Gary Kemp: 'Our parents gave us our sense of responsibility to one another, our moral compass.' Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/16/1366134564973/Martin-and-Gary-Kemp-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Linda Nylind/Guardian") (media:description nil "'Mum and Dad were fantastic ­parents, and they instilled a lot of pride in us, a lot of love.' Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian"))) (item nil (title nil "Bill Bailey: Bill's excellent adventure") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2013/apr/19/bill-bailey-interview-qualmpeddler") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/2539?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abill-bailey-interview-qualmpeddler%3A1893173&ch=Culture&c3=Guardian&c4=Bill+Bailey%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CIndonesia+%28News%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CComedy&c6=Simon+Hattenstone&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A00&c8=1893173&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Bill+Bailey%3A+Bill%27s+excellent+adventure&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FCulture%2FBill+Bailey\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Comedian, musician, actor, educator, saviour of unwanted puppies and endangered owls… you name it, Bill Bailey has been it – and loved every minute</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/bill-bailey\" title=\"\">Bill Bailey</a> hates jokes – always has done. When somebody tells him one, he says, he feels as if he's being mugged – the buildup, the promise that he'll find this one funny, the forced reaction. Ugh. Nothing worse.</p><p>Bailey is possibly the world's least likely rock'n'roll comedian. It's not just the aversion to old-fashioned one-liners; it's the way he tells his non-jokes (cerebral shaggy dog stories that don't always conclude with much of a laugh) and his appearance (shoulder-length half-head of hair and mad, staring eyes, like something out of the Hobbit). But rock'n'roll comedian he is. He sells out stadiums, does world tours, has his share of obsessive fans and struts the stage with guitar in hand. He has a thing for progressive rock, and in a way his epic tours are like classic 1970s concept albums. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2010/nov/10/bill-bailey-review\" title=\"\">Dandelion Mind</a>, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2009/jan/07/bill-bailey-gielgud-review\" title=\"\">Tinselworm</a>, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2004/nov/07/comedy\" title=\"\">Part Troll</a>, Cosmic Jam: even the names of the shows evoke prog rock. In his latest, <a href=\"http://www.billbailey.co.uk/tour/\" title=\"\">Qualmpeddler</a>, he confronts his myriad doubts about the modern world via religious dubstep, folk bouzouki,  <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/higgs-boson\" title=\"\">Higgs boson</a>, rare planetary alignment, Spice Girl reunions and more.</p><p>We meet at his Hammersmith office, which is every bit as bonkers as you might hope. Every object tells an unlikely story. There's the vintage clarinet-reed vending machine picked up in Philadelphia; a load of french horns that he bought as a job lot and turned into wall lights; a massive Bill Bailey Toblerone bar propped up on a grand piano (the manufacturer gave him mountains of the stuff for a piece he was doing about hoarding for the apocalypse); and a huge, terrifying bird.</p><p>What is that owl thing, I ask.</p><p>\"That 'owl thing' is a Eurasian eagle owl.\" It's stuffed, but looks pretty lively at first glance. \"It's a gift from my wife, because we rescued one from a Chinese restaurant last year.\" Where? \"In China. So it's a reminder of that.\"</p><p>How did he rescue an owl from a Chinese restaurant? \"We bought it. It was on the menu. It&nbsp;was a live owl, in a cage, on the menu waiting to be eaten, and we haggled with them for a bit and bought it for $400. We put it in a taxi, drove up to the woods, and let him go. I talk about it in the new show. Our son was with us at the time. He was eight then, and he filmed it on his little camera. There's this very sweet film I show at the end of the standup show, of us releasing this owl. The camera's a bit jiggly, then you see the owl emerge out of this carboard box, and then it flies off.\"</p><p>The stuffed owl in the office is massive. \"Yes,\" Bailey says. \"It is. It's the largest. My wife Kristin is a collector of oddities like this.\" Are you sure this isn't the owl that was on the menu? He grins. \"It may be! I&nbsp;am quite tempted to bring it out at the end of the show and say, 'We changed our minds! We were going to release it, but we thought no, fuck it, it looks much nicer in the office.' \"</p><p>This being Bailey, he's not quite finished yet. There's a bit more knowledge to impart. \"The Eurasian eagle owl is an apex predator, so you can release them anywhere in the world and they would be fine. An apex predator means that nothing preys on it.\" There follows a quick class on apex predators, humans, jaguars and the South American jungles.</p><p>He has an astonishing ability to soak up obscure knowledge and incorporate it into his act. As a boy, he says, his mind was a sponge. He grew up in Bath as Mark Bailey – he was nicknamed Bill by his music teacher, becase he played the song <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ET1X96SyWMI\" title=\"\">Won't You Come Home, Bill Bailey</a> so beautifully on his guitar. He was an only child, to a doctor father and nurse mother, and spent much of his time chatting with adults, mining them for knowledge. He sees his own son, also an only child, doing the same thing now. He'd tell tall stories, and often wonder how he'd dreamed them. \"You spend a lot more time on your own as an only child. And there's space to allow your imagination to take flight. If&nbsp;you're bouncing ideas off someone, you take it one way and they take it another, wherereas if it's just you, there are no constraints.\"</p><p>Was he ridiculously clever? \"I won't lie to you,\" he says. \"At school I found it easy. Every year I got the prize.\" Was it a posh school? \"Not particularly – it was direct grant. All boys. And every year for the first three years they said, 'OK, the English prize is Bailey', then geography, history, maths, physics, everything. One year I won them all.\"</p><p>His fellow pupils must have despised him. \"They did. 'Ah, you bloody swot.'\" It gets worse,&nbsp;Bailey says. He&nbsp;wasn't simply brilliant academically – he was great at everything. \"One year I was captain of the cricket team, and the lead in the school play. Fair play to the English teacher who decided on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Resistible_Rise_of_Arturo_Ui\" title=\"\">The Resistible Rise Of Arturo Ui</a> – good on yer.\" Bailey's never been backwards at coming forwards: even today, his promotional material stresses that he's not simply messing about with comedy music – he's pitch-perfect.</p><p>Did he hate himself for being good at everything? \"I sort of did. I rebelled against it, and by the fourth and fifth year I just went off the rails.\" He stopped trying, stopped winning prizes, and joined a band. Going off the rails is all relative, though – he still managed to get an A in his English A-level. He started studying for an English degree, but gave up after a year. \"I was restless. I&nbsp;wanted to get on, be challenged a bit more. I suppose there is a natural sense of rebellion somewhere along the line. At school, I&nbsp;was bored with the teachers, and there were moments where I felt they were singling me out… I suppose because they thought, 'Oh, here's a student we can get great results with', and I&nbsp;resolutely refused to go along with it. The same at university. I just got bored with it.\"</p><p>For a decade or so, he drifted, travelling across&nbsp;the globe in search of the meaning of life (spending lots of time in Indonesia, where he's off to later this afternoon), following any hippyish trail he came across, but also working – touring with a theatre company, playing in bands, doing comedy.</p><p>Back then, he even told jokes. Lots of them: short and punchy, the ones he can't stand. He was part of a double act, working at the <a href=\"http://www.jokerclub.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Joker Comedy Club in Southend</a>. One night in 1994 the owner rang to tell him the closing act had dropped out and asked if Bailey could do an emergency shift.</p><p>\"But my partner Martin was on holiday. He said, 'Can't you just do it on your own?' I&nbsp;went, 'I&nbsp;don't know if I can', and he said, 'Well, here's the money', and I went, 'Oh, I get the same money if it's just me! I'll do it.\"</p><p>He did the gig, and it was disastrous. \"The Joker is quite raucous: they like their comedy and they let you know one way or the other. Then some bloke said, 'Oi, mate, tell us a joke!' I&nbsp;thought, 'Oh my God, I can't think of any jokes at all.' So I went, 'OK, three blokes went into a pub', and straight away there was attention because this was something the audience could respond to.\"</p><p>The problem was, there wasn't a joke at the end of it. He&nbsp;didn't have a clue what he would say next.</p><p>\"I'm thinking, 'I'm so in the shit here.' So I said, 'I say three – it was probably more like four or five', and that got a couple of laughs. Then I said, 'Well, I say five – it was 10. OK, 10 blokes go in a pub', and I&nbsp;say, 'OK, there were quite a few more than that – 20-30 blokes', and then it was 100, 200, a village, a small town, an area of Holland, northern Europe, and it went on and on, extrapolating this thing from three to most sentient blokes. 'OK, the entire male population of the world goes into a pub and the first bloke goes up to the bar, and says, I'll get these.' And I&nbsp;said, 'What an idiot!' And it got a huge laugh, and I&nbsp;thought: that just came out of nowhere.\"</p><p>It was a revelation. Bailey realised that was what he actually enjoyed – deconstructing humour. And if he could get a laugh in the process, so much the better. \"What I'd been doing up till then was not really what I'd been wanting to do. It was like a facsimile of a comedy act: it was what we'd seen other people do. It was jokes and one-liners and songs, but it wasn't really what I wanted to do. I'd settled for it.\"</p><p>He thought if he'd managed to dismantle a&nbsp;joke&nbsp;in front of such a tough, beery crowd, he&nbsp;could develop this. So he went on to tell jokes&nbsp;set&nbsp;in the 1950s, in Shakespearean and Chaucerian times, about all sorts of unlikely subjects – and the skill of these anti-jokes lay in the telling rather than in the punchline, which often didn't exist anyway.</p><p>What happened to poor Martin? \"Well, he came back from holiday, and we did some more gigs, and then I said, 'I want to do this on my own now', and he said, 'Yeah, all right, fine.' We parted amicably. He went on to work for a photo archivist, which suited him down to the ground, because he was obsessed with cataloguing.\"</p><p>So Bailey had become an accidental surrealist. And after a long wait, his career took off quickly. In 1995, he won a Time Out comedy award; the next year he was shortlisted for the Perrier at Edinburgh. His act was more wordy than Proust, his humour was clever and gentle, most of his non-jokes were accompanied by music, and he appealed to people who liked to think of themselves as being on the smart side. He was also virtually impossible to categorise. I&nbsp;ask if he can explain his humour. And he's stumped.</p><p>\"Well …\" He takes a deep breath. \"It's a mixture of different elements: straightforward standup, observational, a bit of politics, a bit of philosophical discourse, a bit of interaction with the audience where I try to subvert the nature of&nbsp;audience participation. Then there are various musical sections of the show, where the music is&nbsp;observational, so it's not a parody per se: the music is the joke. So, for example, I bemoan the&nbsp;fact that the church has lost its influence in&nbsp;society – the church was always a big part of my childhood; now people don't take it seriously. The church has lost touch with the youth, they need to try to re-engage, so I&nbsp;imagine writing a piece to promote the church using dubstep, so we have an organ section, which turns into dubstep, which turns into an animated film in which the Archbishop of Canterbury turns into a ball of hair, which kills the devil with lightning... Hahahaha!\" He's laughing not at the sketch, but at the impossibility of explaining it. \"I can see your problem.\"</p><p>Has he ever tried to break it down like this before? \"No! No! I'm trying to draw the elements together.\" Cognitive dissonance apparently comes into it somewhere – \"something we all experience, but we maybe don't know we do\".</p><p>Now I'm having to ask him for an explanation of his explanation. What's cognitive dissonance? \"It's when there are two opposing thoughts in your head which seem to cancel each other out, yet you're able to hold them simultaneously. Smoking is a classsic one. 'This is bad for me; I&nbsp;like smoking.' You recognise the dissonance in those two thoughts. So I say to the audience, 'You all know what this is', and they think they don't, but they do. <em>That's</em> what I&nbsp;like to do,\" he says with a click of his fingers, as if he's just got it. \"I get people to realise that they know all these things.\"</p><p>Because he's so mellow most of the time, it's easy to forget that Bailey is a political comedian – or at least a comedian with politics. Once, when he was asked what he thought about Tony Blair, he found himself on the front pages. \"I&nbsp;just came out with some involuntary eruption. Among the general ranting, it came out as 'warmongering legacy junkie'. It could equally have been 'legacy-mongering war junkie'.\" But, he says, his contempt for Blair is nothing compared with that for today's government. When he turns to George Osborne and David Cameron, he's almost incoherent with rage. \"This is different. This is more like a horror, a deep horror: to see how this confidence trick is being played out in front of everybody. It's evil genius. The hideous, two-headed Osborne-Cameron creature just frightening you with the utterly amoral … It's almost brilliant, the way they have turned our justified and rightful anger against bankers on to 'benefit scroungers'. How do they do that?\" He comes to a stop, bewildered.</p><p>There's something <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/historyofthebbc/resources/in-depth/reith_1.shtml\" title=\"\">Reithian</a> about his humour, I&nbsp;suggest: inform, entertain and educate. \"Yeah! Yeah! I&nbsp;do have that,\" he says enthusiastically. \"I&nbsp;want it to be more than you just come and have a laugh. Obviously, first and foremost, that's what it's about – people pay their money and they want to have a laugh and take their mind off the fact that the high street is closing down and their <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/jan/11/jessops-shuts-stores-1370-job-losses\" title=\"\">Jessops vouchers are no longer valid</a>. But there's also a&nbsp;bit of wanting people to come along and go away with something. 'You know what? I know what cognitive dissonance is now. I know who wrote this piece of music.' \"</p><p>Bailey has thoroughly enjoyed his success, not&nbsp;least because it made his parents happy. For&nbsp;a&nbsp;long time, they had patiently watched him drift from continent to continent, dabbling in the&nbsp;performing arts. Even though they never said&nbsp;as much, they must have wondered what on earth he&nbsp;was doing with his life. After all, they were practical people with serious jobs and a Protestant work ethic. \"I&nbsp;think they were concerned, more than anything, because comedy seemed to be a very uncertain future. Then they heard me on Radio 4, and they were like, 'Oh, that seems to have a bit more substance to it.'&nbsp; \"</p><p>His mother died in 2005, but his 80-year-old father still enjoys his shows. (\"We have got a similar humour. He's into surreal, odd stuff.\") As&nbsp;does his nine-year-old son, Dax, who has already started heckling him at gigs. He says Dax is so used to seeing him introduced on stage that whenever he comes across a microphone, he feels compelled to do the honours. \"We were on holiday recently and found this karaoke bar, and he just took over. He had the mic and he was like, 'OK, we're going to take a short break and we'll be back in 10 minutes,' then he introduced me.\" Bailey says he was so taken aback that he couldn't think of anything to do but perform, so he and Dax did a duet.</p><p>Bailey met his wife in 1987 at one of his&nbsp;gigs when he was a jobbing comedian. Kristin, who is now responsible for his business affairs, was running a bar in Edinburgh. He wooed the former costume designer with a weekly letter for 12 months till she finally weakened. In 1998, they married on a whim in Banda, Indonesia. Dax is named after an Indonesian friend. The three of them share a house down the road from his office&nbsp;with four parrots, two monkeys, a python, a&nbsp;chameleon, a few fish, two starlings, a number of cats and five rescue dogs (three of which he had&nbsp;shipped over from Indonesia).</p><p>Now 49, he had to wait until he was 31 for his first sniff of success, but before long he was omnipresent – and not just as a comedian. There was Bill Bailey the actor (notably alongside Dylan Moran in the TV series <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/black-books\" title=\"\">Black Books</a>), the panel show fixture (pop quiz <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006v0dz\" title=\"\">Never Mind The Buzzcocks</a>), the ornithologist (<a href=\"http://sky1.sky.com/bill-baileys-birdwatching-bonanza-2\" title=\"\">Bill Bailey's Birdwatching Bonanza</a>), the natural historian (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eyaWpZeGYTU\" title=\"\">Baboons With Bill Bailey</a>), the music instructor (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2008/oct/17/comedy\" title=\"\">Bill Bailey's Remarkable Guide To The Orchestra</a>). And now there's Bill Bailey the champion of forgotten heroes: <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0160nxk\" title=\"\">he has just made a two-part documentary about Alfred Russel Wallace</a>, Darwin's colleague and rival, and co-originator of the theory of evolution.</p><p>Bailey loves doing the non-funny stuff. \"I was in Jakarta recently doing a talk at the Indonesian Heritage Society about Wallace … There were no laughs in it. It was just a talk about something I&nbsp;felt passionate about. There were a&nbsp;couple of nods of appreciation, that's all, and I&nbsp;felt great at the end of it. Quite satisfied.\" He loves to escape the confines of comedy, the tyranny of the laugh.</p><p>As he's talking, I find myself staring at a creepy Bill Bailey mask. \"Ah yes,\" he says with a smile. \"I&nbsp;was headlining the Saturn stage at Knebworth, and headlining the Apollo stage was <a href=\"http://www.slipknot1.com/\" title=\"\">Slipknot</a>. I&nbsp;thought, because Slipknot's trademark is scary masks, I'd have my own Slipknot mask made of myself.\" He tries it on, and he does look genuinely scary. But not for long.</p><p>I offer him a Malteser. \"But I was just about to offer you a Belgian chocolate biscuit. I'll see your Malteser and raise you a Belgian Titbit.\"</p><p>There's something heartening about Bailey's success. After all, comedy can be such a ruthless, backstabbing world. Do you have to be a show-off to get on? \"Undoubtedly. I don't think any comic could say there isn't a bit of them that doesn't want to show off. You have to have that, otherwise you can't really do it.\" Do you have to be tough? \"You have to have a thick skin, yes. If&nbsp;you're going to do something as foolhardy as standup, you've got to be able to take it on the chin if someone has a go at you.\" Is he really thick-skinned? \"Probably not. But I am resilient.\"</p><p>It's easy to imagine Bailey as a much loved university lecturer – perhaps professor of music, popular entertainment, natural history and joke-free comedy. Has he ever fancied an alternative career? \"No, because the stage allows comics a certain freedom of expression that you don't get anywhere else. You can say whatever you want – it's the last bastion of free speech in some ways. So I feel there's an obligation to make it that bit more interesting …\" He clicks his fingers impatiently, searching for his words. \"A bit more about something, a bit more challenging, for me and the audience.\"</p><p>Bailey puts on his coat on and says he's got to be off now – he's going straight to Indonesia. How's he getting there? \"The 209. Goes all the way to Jakarta!\" That sounds dangerously like a joke. He apologises, locks the door behind him and heads off down the road to south-east Asia.</p><p>• Bill Bailey's Qualmpeddler is touring from Friday until 3 November; go to <a href=\"http://www.billbailey.co.uk\" title=\"\">billbailey.co.uk</a> for details. Bill Bailey's Jungle Hero airs on BBC2 at 8pm tomorrow and next Sunday.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/bill-bailey\">Bill Bailey</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/indonesia\">Indonesia</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/simonhattenstone\">Simon Hattenstone</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Bill Bailey") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Indonesia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Interviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 14:00:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2013/apr/19/bill-bailey-interview-qualmpeddler") (dc:creator nil "Simon Hattenstone") (dc:subject nil "Culture") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T14:00:02Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407092692") (media:keywords nil "Bill Bailey, Comedy, Indonesia, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366129425340/Bill-Bailey-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Jaap Scheeren/Guardian") (media:description nil "Bailey in his London office: 'If you're going to do something as foolhardy as standup, you've got to be able to take it on the chin if someone has a go at you.' Photograph: Jaap Scheeren for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366129432290/Bill-Bailey-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Jaap Scheeren/Guardian") (media:description nil "Bailey in his London office: ‘If you’re going to do something as foolhardy as standup, you’ve got to be able to take it on the chin if someone has a go at you.’ Photograph: Jaap Scheeren for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "550") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "363") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366129420599/Bill-Bailey-001.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Jaap Scheeren/Guardian") (media:description nil "Photograph: Jaap Scheeren for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366129975703/Bailey-in-Edinburgh-in-20-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Rex Features; Getty Images; Channel 4") (media:description nil "Bailey in Edinburgh in 2003, with his son Dax in 2011, and in Black Books. Photographs: Rex Features; Getty Images; Channel 4"))) (item nil (title nil "Broken news: how to get through a major cable TV news event | Bob Garfield") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/broken-news-cable-tv-news-event") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/61888?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abroken-news-cable-tv-news-event%3A1896029&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Media%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CUS+television+industry%2CUS+news%2CWorld+news&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CUS+Elections%2CTV&c6=Bob+Garfield&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+01%3A00&c8=1896029&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Broken+news%3A+how+to+get+through+a+major+cable+TV+news+event&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">It's been a big news week – and a long one for ill-served viewers. Here's a survival guide from one weathered veteran</p><p>The marathon coverage of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a> has set into motion the all-too-familiar. When something awful happens, the human impulse is get informed instantly. That often means rushing to a TV and gaping at the unfolding drama. It's an understandable reflex, but usually, a self-defeating one, like scratching a sore or drinking sea water.</p><p>It may satisfy the immediate urge, but beware the consequences. CNN's false report about arrests was as predictable as it was irresponsible; live TV coverage is a world of blunder. So, if you must tune into 24-hour cable news for the latest, there a few things always to bear in mind:</p><p><strong>A watched pot never boils.</strong> Following violent crimes and disasters, the intensity of the coverage is inversely correlated with the prospects for advancing the story. Incidents last as long as they last – usually, seconds – then they are over. The \"when\" and \"where\" and some of the \"who\" (victims) are immediately obvious. The rest of the \"who\" (the culprits, the missing), plus the \"why\" and the \"how\", can take days or weeks or months to unravel. </p><p><strong>The latest developments usually aren't.</strong> Desperate to add to the endlessly repeated basic facts, reporters will breathlessly pass along tiny bits of detail gleaned from authorities speaking unofficially, possible witnesses and cousins of possible witnesses. Do not be fooled by the urgency in the journalists' voices. The details are second or third hand and usually wrong. \"Unconfirmed report\" means \"not true\". \"Confirmed report\" means \"probably not true\".</p><p><strong>Get your brain a screen saver.</strong> That's what computers use to keep a single image from being etched into the screen. If a tragic news event is caught on video, TV will show you again and again what happened until it is forever burned into your consciousness. Eventually, this denudes even the most shocking footage of any informational or emotional clout – not to mention, meaning – and turns it into little more than a GIF. If you absolutely must hang on to every word, consider switching to the radio.</p><p><strong>If you knew what went on in the kitchen, you might not eat at the restaurant.</strong> The cable channels have a handful of anchors and a handful of reporters. They may look authoritative, but they don't constitute anything remotely like a robust news-gathering machine. The channels do employ a whole mess of producers, but their principal job is to book experts and pundits, who may have credentials and make-up, but are basically just guessing.</p><p><strong>Bad news does not necessarily have larger significance.</strong> When calamity erupts, your favorite network will be live on the scene for hours or days. Logos will be designed. Concern will be etched on the anchors' faces. Thoughts and prayers will be expressed for victims and their kin. But neither the amount of airtime nor even the body count are reliable measures of intrinsic importance. A fatal spasm of violence (in the west only), or a mass shooting, or even a missing blond person (if cute), will always trump, for instance, a budget vote or telecom lobbying or other events lacking yellow police tape that affect a large percentage of the population every day. As the saying goes: if it bleeds it leads. The corollary is: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Citizens_United_v._Federal_Election_Commission\">Citizens United</a> – the supreme court ruling that fundamentally altered the scale and transparency of US political campaign funding – didn't get a logo.</p><p><strong><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/They_Shoot_Horses,_Don't_They%3F_(novel)\">They shoot horses, don't they?</a></strong> You've seen film of the dance marathons from the 1930s – those desperate people circling the floor for hour on end, day and night, in the hopes of winning some pitiful prize. When you tune into 24-hour cable after a tragedy, ask yourself the question: \"There is nothing being accomplished through this awful spectacle, so why am I watching?\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/ustelevision\">US television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/bob-garfield\">Bob Garfield</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "US television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "US television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 12:00:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/broken-news-cable-tv-news-event") (dc:creator nil "Bob Garfield") (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T12:00:07Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407453623") (media:keywords nil "Media, US television, US television industry, United States, World news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366299222799/Video-grab-from-CNN-of-th-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Wang Lei/Xinhua Press/Corbis") (media:description nil "Video grab from CNN of the explosions at the Boston Marathon, Monday 15 April 2013. Photograph: Wang Lei/Xinhua Press/Corbis")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366299233213/Video-grab-from-CNN-of-th-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Wang Lei/Xinhua Press/Corbis") (media:description nil "Video grab from CNN of the explosions at the Boston Marathon, Monday 15 April 2013. Photograph: Wang Lei/Xinhua Press/Corbis"))) (item nil (title nil "Transformers 4 mounts reality TV search for Chinese wannabe actors") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2013/apr/19/transformers-4-reality-tv-china") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/71312?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Atransformers-4-reality-tv-china%3A1896317&ch=Film&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Action+and+adventure+%28Film+genre%29%2CScience+fiction+and+fantasy+%28Film+genre%29%2CMichael+Bay%2CMark+Wahlberg%2CFilm%2CParamount+Pictures%2CReality+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CCulture%2CChina+%28News%29%2CAsia+Pacific+%28News%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFilm+Reviews&c6=Ben+Child&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+11%3A59&c8=1896317&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Transformers+4+mounts+reality+TV+search+for+Chinese+wannabe+actors&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FFilm%2FAction+and+adventure\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Michael Bay's robot franchise capitalises on popularity in China with reality TV recruitment show</p><p>Transformers 4, the latest instalment in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/michael-bay\" title=\"\">Michael Bay</a>'s interminable giant robot saga, is to recruit four Chinese actors <a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/transformers-4-paramount-cast-chinese-441636\" title=\"\">via a reality TV talent search</a>.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/feedarticle/10728706\" title=\"\">Studio Paramount announced earlier this month</a> that the film will be a US-Chinese co-production, a nod to the franchise's huge popularity in China. Recent instalment <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/140386/transformers\" title=\"\">Transformers: Dark of the Moon</a> stands as the fourth-highest-grossing film ever in China with a haul of $165m (£108m) in 2011.</p><p></p><p>Transformers 4 Chinese Actor Talent Search was launched at a press conference in Beijing this week. US judges will include Transformers producer Lorenzo DiBonaventura and former Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences chief Sid Ganis, who now chairs Jiaflix Enterprises, a partner production company on the film.</p><p></p><p>Ganis said the show would \"give actors and fans of the Transformers franchise the opportunity to appear in a major motion picture, and it will provide the world audience yet another glimpse of the Chinese people, the Chinese culture and China itself\".</p><p>Judges are hoping to find two trained actors and two with no previous on-screen experience to join other Chinese cast members for the film. Local judges will include representatives from Transformers 4's Chinese co-producers, China Movie Channel, and the website where wannabe contestants can register for the show.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2012/nov/09/mark-wahlberg-transformers-4\" title=\"\">Mark Wahlberg is the lead</a> in the new movie, having replaced <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/shia-labeouf\" title=\"\">Shia LaBeouf</a>. Bay announced in November that the star of Boogie Nights and The Departed had been given the role following a successful stint on his forthcoming bodybuilding-themed action comedy Pain & Gain.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/actionandadventure\">Action and adventure</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/sciencefictionandfantasy\">Science fiction and fantasy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/michael-bay\">Michael Bay</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/mark-wahlberg\">Mark Wahlberg</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/paramount-pictures\">Paramount Pictures</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/reality-tv\">Reality TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/china\">China</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/asia-pacific\">Asia Pacific</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/benchild\">Ben Child</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Action and adventure") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Science fiction and fantasy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Michael Bay") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Mark Wahlberg") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Film") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Paramount Pictures") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Reality TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "China") (cate