aph Media Group, Newspapers & magazines, Television, Television & radio, News Corporation, 20th Century Fox, Podcasting, Money, Kickstarter, Radio, US public radio, Ben Elton, Bill Bailey") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366104787539/North-Korea-Undercover-Pa-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC") (media:description nil "North Korea Undercover: the audience represents a massive 69% increase on the usual average number of viewers for Panorama, Photograph: BBC")) (media:content ((duration . "2153") (fileSize . "34707869") (type . "audio/mpeg") (url . "http://download.guardian.co.uk/audio/kip/media/series/mediatalk/1366305931329/9063/gdn.med.130419.mh.panorama-harding-defamation.mp3")))) (item nil (title nil "TV highlights 19/04/2013") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/da-vincis-demons-oliver-stone") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/25846?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ada-vincis-demons-oliver-stone%3A1895868&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CLeonardo+da+Vinci%2COliver+Stone%2CCulture&c5=Art%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CFilm+Reviews%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Mark+Jones%2CAndrew+Mueller%2CBen+Arnold%2CJohn+Robinson%2CAli+Catterall%2CDavid+Stubbs%2CGwilym+Mumford+%28contributor%29&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1895868&c9=Article&c10=&c13=Watch+this+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=TV+highlights+19%2F04%2F2013&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Live Gymnastics | Unreported World | Ice Road Truckers | The Ice Cream Girls | The Genius Of Josiah Wedgwood | Oliver Stone's Untold History Of The United States | Not Going Out | Da Vinci's Demons</p><h2>Live Gymnastics: European Championships<br />1pm, BBC2<br /></h2><p>Matt Baker presents coverage of the prestigious event from Moscow's Olimpiyskiy national sports complex. Live action this afternoon includes the women's all-around competition, with Great Britain's four-strong team due to feature senior debutantes Gabby Jupp and Charlie Fellows. Also, there are highlights of the men's all-around discipline, with several of the celebrated London 2012 Team GB squad getting set to slap chalk on their hands. <em>Mark Jones</em></p><p></p><h2>Unreported World<br />7.30pm, Channel 4<br /></h2><p>Aidan Hartley reports from Gilgil, Kenya, a small town with a hefty population of homeless children. Many of them descended on Gilgil five years ago, after being orphaned and/or displaced by the ethnic violence that beset the country following disputed elections. Hartley meets some of the kids and falls in with the Restart Centre, one of those quietly heroic local outfits dedicated to making a bad place a bit better. Inevitably, their resources are smaller in scale than the problem they're attempting to tackle. <em>Andrew Mueller</em></p><p></p><h2>Ice Road Truckers<br />8pm, Channel 5<br /></h2><p>It's the season five finale of Ice Road Truckers and the ice is melting, which may mean that spring is on the way but also makes it among the most perilous times to navigate the roads of the frozen northern US and Canada. In Manitoba, Rick and Hugh are hoping to make it home in one piece for another season; but, in fairly predictable fashion, things don't quite go to plan. Meanwhile, over in Fairbanks – and following Dave's dismissal last week – the winner of the load count for the season is up for grabs. <em>Ben Arnold</em></p><p></p><h2><strong>The Ice Cream Girls</strong><br />9pm, ITV<br /></h2><p>Dorothy Koomson's international bestseller receives a welcome three-part transition to the small screen. Under very different circumstances, two women return to the coastal resort where they grew up, 17 years on from accusations that they murdered their duplicitous ratbag schoolteacher. Poppy (Jodhi May) has spent that time in prison after being convicted, while Serena (Lorraine Burroughs) returns with the life and family built during her years of freedom, desperate to avoid her past. A captivating first act. <em>MJ</em></p><h2><strong>The Genius Of Josiah Wedgwood</strong><br />9pm, BBC2<br /></h2><p>Wedgwood, we know, made nice pottery, but this documentary by historian and author AN Wilson aims to prove that he was more than just a potter; and, tacitly, to prove that Wilson himself is more than just a plum for hire. Wilson's father worked at Wedgwood in the 1950s, and the multiplicity of Josiah's talents (artist, chemist, philanthropist) has captivated the presenter since childhood. Wilson's narrative attempts a bit too much, but Wedgwood's achievements still gleam through the clutter. <em>John Robinson</em></p><h2>Oliver Stone's Untold History Of The United States<br />9pm, Sky Atlantic<br /></h2><p>With his reputation for muck-raking and provocation, Oliver Stone feels a good fit for this 10-part parallel history of the US, which, the director assures us in a rather portentous introduction, will \"tell the American story that has never been told before\". Stone begins with the second world war, arguing that the allies' eventual victory was a result of Soviet stamina rather than American interventionism. Nothing terribly radical here, but it's urgently told nonetheless. <em>Gwilym Mumford</em></p><p></p><h2>Not Going Out<br />9.30pm, BBC1<br /></h2><p>Lucy is taking a course in counselling. This, of course, is a red rag to Lee's pawing, snorting, unreconstructed bull, who soon takes up the challenge to be her guinea pig, with the ultimate aim of getting his leg over. It's an overly familiar setup and one that makes those frequent comparisons between Not Going Out and Men Behaving Badly seem justified. At any rate, it soon transpires that Lee has father issues, in the shape and size of Bobby Ball, who might well be able to shed some light on matters. <em>Ali Catterall</em></p><p></p><h2><strong>Da Vinci's Demons</strong><br />10pm, FOX<br /></h2><p>David Goyer, co-writer of the Dark Knight trilogy, is responsible for this new drama, which steals some of the commercial heat from The Da Vinci Code. Reimagining 15th-century Florence as alluringly sumptuous but fetid with intrigue, vice and murder, it stars Tom Riley as the artist, cutting an almost swashbuckling presence as he seeks to expose the lies of religion, undermine the dominance of the elite and make peace with his father. Liberties are taken with history, and the dialogue can be risibly portentous, but it's sexily watchable. <em>David Stubbs</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/davinci\">Leonardo da Vinci</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/oliver-stone\">Oliver Stone</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mark-jones\">Mark Jones</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/andrewmueller\">Andrew Mueller</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/ben-arnold\">Ben Arnold</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/johnrobinson\">John Robinson</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/alicatterall\">Ali Catterall</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/davidstubbs\">David Stubbs</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/gwilym-mumford\">Gwilym Mumford</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserve