onardo and Laura Haddock as Lucrezia Donati in Da Vinci's Demons. Photograph: Greg Wiliiams/Starz Entertainment"))) (item nil (title nil "Jennifer Lawrence among Time's 100 most influential people") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2013/apr/18/jennifer-lawrence-time-magazine") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/3663?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajennifer-lawrence-time-magazine%3A1896141&ch=Film&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Jennifer+Lawrence+%28film%29%2CFilm%2CCulture%2CMedia%2CTime+magazine%2CDaniel+Day-Lewis+%28Film%29%2CSteven+Spielberg+%28Film%29%2CJodie+Foster%2CBryan+Cranston%2CBeyonce%2CJustin+Timberlake%2CGirls+%28TV+show%29%2CBreaking+Bad&c5=Press+Media%2CUnclassified%2CPop+Music%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CFilm+Reviews&c6=Henry+Barnes&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+06%3A54&c8=1896141&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Jennifer+Lawrence+among+Time%27s+100+most+influential+people&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FFilm%2FJennifer+Lawrence\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Oscar-winning actor (called 'a gem with a killer stare' in a citation by Jodie Foster) joins Daniel Day-Lewis, Bryan Cranston, Kate Middleton … and Barack Obama on the annual magazine list</p><p>Jennifer Lawrence, Daniel Day-Lewis and Steven Spielberg have been named amongst the most influential people in the world by Time magazine.</p><p>The US news weekly, which<a href=\"http://time100.time.com/\"> annually publishes a list of the 100 key players</a> in politics, science and the arts, also included Girls writer and actor Lena Dunham and Breaking Bad actor Bryan Cranston in their list. </p><p>Lawrence, this year's best actress Oscar-winner thanks to her scene-stealing turn in David O Russell's Silver Linings Playbook, received an <a href=\"http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/jennifer-lawrence/\">adulatory write-up</a> from fellow actor Jodie Foster. </p><p>\"You'll remember where you were when you first felt it,\" wrote Foster, who directed Lawrence in her film The Beaver. \"How you were stuck to one spot like a small animal considering its end. The Jennifer Lawrence Stare.\"</p><p>Lawrence, according to Foster, is variously \"ballsy\", \"a spritely tomboy\", \"a hoot\" and \"a gem with a killer stare\".   </p><p>\"Sure, this girl can act,\" wrote Foster. \"But, man, this girl can also just be.\"</p><p>Day-Lewis, also an Oscar winner this year thanks to his role in Spielberg's Lincoln biopic, was described as \"a deep-sea creature who's unexpectedly approachable and thoroughly delightful company\" by the film's scriptwriter Tony Kushner. </p><p>\"The power and grace of Daniel's performances seem to emanate from something he's made contact with, deep within, intensely private and specific to his experience but also mysteriously universal,\" he continued.</p><p>The list is not ranked, but is divided into the categories Titans, Leaders, Pioneers, Icons and Artists. Neither Lawrence nor Spielberg (Artists both) have made it onto the Icon list. Day-Lewis shares that honour with Beyonce, Justin Timberlake and Kate Middleton.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/jennifer-lawrence\">Jennifer Lawrence</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/time-magazine\">Time magazine</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/danieldaylewis\">Daniel Day-Lewis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/stevenspielberg\">Steven Spielberg</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/jodie-foster\">Jodie Foster</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/bryan-cranston\">Bryan Cranston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/beyonce\">Beyoncé</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/justin-timberlake\">Justin Timberlake</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/girls\">Girls</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/breaking-bad\">Breaking Bad</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/henrybarnes\">Henry Barnes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Jennifer Lawrence") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Film") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Time magazine") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Daniel Day-Lewis") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Steven Spielberg") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Jodie Foster") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Bryan Cranston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/music")) "Beyoncé") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Justin Timberlake") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Girls") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Breaking Bad") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 17:54:05 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2013/apr/18/jennifer-lawrence-time-magazine") (dc:creator nil "Henry Barnes") (dc:subject nil "Film") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T17:54:05Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407461985") (media:keywords nil "Jennifer Lawrence, Film, Culture, Media, Time magazine, Daniel Day-Lewis, Steven Spielberg, Jodie Foster, Bryan Cranston, Beyoncé, Justin Timberlake, Girls, Breaking Bad") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Film/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306503324/Jennifer-Lawrence-and-Jod-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Jennifer Lawrence and Jodie Foster on set of The Beaver")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Film/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306509837/Jennifer-Lawrence-and-Jod-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "'She can also just be' … Jennifer Lawrence and Jodie Foster with Anton Yelchin on set of The Beaver"))) (item nil (title nil "Yemi Ajibade obituary") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/18/yemi-ajibade-obituary") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91498?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ayemi-ajibade-obituary%3A1896039&ch=From+the+Guardian&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Stage%2CCulture%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media%2CTheatre&c6=Femi+Elufowoju+Jr&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+05%3A57&c8=1896039&c9=Article&c10=Obituary&c13=Other+lives+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Yemi+Ajibade+obituary&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FFrom+the+Guardian%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>When the BBC producer John Stockbridge was approached by the World Service in the 60s to create a drama for African listeners, he chose Yemi Ajibade, a promising young actor from west Africa with an established theatre career, for the lead role. The series was never made, but from then onwards Yemi, who has died aged 82, regularly featured on radio. His talent was spotted, too, by television producers and he appeared in series including Danger Man (1965), Dixon of Dock Green (1968), The Black Safari (1972) and The Fosters (1976).</p><p>Yemi's play Parcel Post (1976) explored the clash of traditional African virtues with the values of modern Britain. It was directed by Donald Howarth at the Royal Court in London and, during the theatre's 50th birthday celebrations in 2006, Howarth recalled that the play had a \"reconditioning\" effect on audiences. Among Yemi's other stage plays were Fingers Only (1982), Waiting for Hannibal (1986), Para Ginto (1995) – Peer Gynt transposed to African soil – and A Long Way From Home (1991).</p><p>Yemi was born in Otta, Nigeria, from a line of Yoruba kings. The foundations of his love for theatre and the arts were laid at Abeokuta grammar school. In the mid-1950s Yemi travelled to the UK intending to become a journalist, but read a book on Stanislavsky and thought: \"This is it.\" Yemi joined the Actors' Workshop in 1960 and the London School of Film Technique (now the London Film School) in 1966. Later, he took a master's degree at Royal Holloway, University of London.</p><p>In 1995 Jude Kelly, as artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse, invited Yemi to join the cast of Wole Soyinka's Beatification of Area Boy as part of the Africa 95 celebration. His final stage appearance was on the Olivier stage at the National theatre in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2007/aug/29/theatre1\" title=\"\">Thea Sharrock's 2007 production of Emperor Jones</a>.</p><p>Yemi inspired a younger generation of Nigerian writers and artists in the UK. I first met him in 1991 at Bush House for a BBC World Service radio drama recording. He became a firm source of encouragement and in subsequent years attended every production I produced or directed. During its 10th anniversary All African Stars Gala (2008) at Theatre Royal Stratford East, the British-African theatre company Tiata Fahodzi (which I founded) recognised his contribution to British theatre.</p><p>He is survived by his wife, the actor and poet Ebony White, and their two daughters, Adenrele and Mimi; another daughter, Marigold, from a previous relationship; and three sisters, Arinade Victoria, Layo and Janet.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage")) "Stage") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Obituaries") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 16:57:15 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/18/yemi-ajibade-obituary") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "From the Guardian") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T16:57:15Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407454367") (media:keywords nil "Stage, Culture, Radio, Television & radio, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Gua