obia; a man in a suit who trips up again and again; a comedy Frenchman saying \"bonjour\"; a machine that digs itself into a hole, dies, and then gets bought for £20,000 by a man named Ron; and&nbsp;more.</p><p>It's not just about the Channel tunnel, though. It's about hot Irish men, \"with iron in their arms and their buttocks\", building the London underground. It's about the tunnels under the Thames, and Swampy, and David Bellamy, and badgers, and a man named Don who watches the badgers.</p><p>It doesn't all work. At times it's hard even to know what Baker is on about. Some of it I think might actually be wrong (like the Dartford tunnel may have two lanes but these days they both head north, so, contrary to what DB says, the only way IS Essex). Who cares though, because so much of it is a joy. The word \"buttocks\" IS funny, as are men called Ron and Don; though not as funny as a man in a suit tripping over, on repeat; and the sentence: \"So you'd recommend fish-farming in a German war tunnel, then?\" from some old footage from the Channel Islands, is one of the greatest ever uttered.</p><p>It comes out so fast too. It's as if there's a fire hydrant on Baker's forehead, it's turned on full, connected to a high pressure hose and aimed at you, and you're being splurt-blasted by his words and wit and wisdom. No, maybe not wisdom. Imagination, then, and a lot of weird stuff, some of which is about tunnels. Fabulous. Bring on the bridges next week.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zvx\" title=\"Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right\"><strong>Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right</strong></a> (BBC1) was one of those documentaries that involves a non-expert celebrity going on a journey of discovery triggered partly by events in their own lives. You know the ones. So Maureen's finding out about memory, partly because her father lost his, and she's worried about hers. There's a bit of science, a bit of psychology, a bit of Paul McKenna, quite a lot of blah. She's amiable company, but the film is meandering, inconclusive, unmemorable.</p><p>And <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zqv\" title=\"Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?\"><strong>Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?</strong></a> (BBC2) was one of those what-if documentaries (thankfully, no lame drama element to this one: they're the worst). In fact, more of a what-when one, because this is going to happen. There's going to be a volcanic eruption and half of La Palma, one of the Canary islands, is going to slide into the sea. No great shame, you might think, but this will unleash a massive CGI wave three times the height of the Shard that will take out New York just like in The Day After Tomorrow, though less convincingly because this CGI wave doesn't have a Hollywood budget behind it.</p><p>They're screwed then, over there. What about us, though? Well, not great if you're in Penzance, I'm afraid. Brighton? Touch and go. But tucked away snuggly and smuggly round the corner here in London? I'll be fine, thank you.</p><p><a href=\"http://gu.com/p/3f8h9/tw via @guardian\" title=\" Watch this: TV highlights\">• Watch this: TV highlights</a></p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://tvlistings.guardian.co.uk/default.aspx\" title=\" Full TV listings\">• Full TV listings</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/danny-baker\">Danny Baker</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samwollaston\">Sam Wollaston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Danny Baker") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 06:00:13 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/brushing-up-on-british-tunnels") (dc:creator nil "Sam Wollaston") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T06:00:13Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407461768") (media:keywords nil "Television, Danny Baker, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306163825/Danny-Baker--005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guy Levy/BBC") (media:description nil "More standup than documentary ... Danny Baker's Brushing Up On - British Tunnels. Photograph: Guy Levy/BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306169471/Danny-Baker--010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guy Levy/BBC") (media:description nil "More standup than documentary ... Danny Baker's Brushing Up On - British Tunnels. Photograph: Guy Levy/BBC")))) ("A week in radio: An Afghan story" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/54708?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aeveryday-story-of-afghan-folk%3A1896020&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Afghanistan+%28News%29%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media&c6=Nosheen+Iqbal&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1896020&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Radio+review+%28G2+series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=An+Everyday+Story+of+Afghan+Folk%3B+Archive+on+4%3A+radio+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FAfghanistan\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">This play adapted from an Afghani soap opera would have been great in the 80s, but sounds a bit dull now<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\">An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00hg8dq\" title=\"Archive on 4\">Archive on 4</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/blogs/radiolab-blog/2013/apr/16/distance-of-moon/\" title=\"Radiolab\">Radiolab</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\"><strong>An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</strong></a> returned for a second series on Radio&nbsp;4 this week, filling in the daily 15 minute drama slot with an imagined take on village life on the Af-Pak border. \"Tell your father you want to marry Shireen, addict or not!\" yelled Meera Syal, playing the Pashtun wife of a poor farmer in her stock elderly Indian biddy accent, scolding a daughter with ideas above her station. The idea being education, the station being the school that pompous village leader Akbar Khan is secretly intent on blowing up.</p><p>This sort of thing would have been wonderful in the 80s – a worthy play adapted from an actual Afghani soap opera (<a href=\"http://www.pactradio.com/en/drama/news/bbc-radio-4-to-broadcast-a-season-of-the-pulay-poray-drama.php\" title=\"Pulay Poray\">Pulay Poray</a> in this case), boiling down the nuances of life and culture on the borderlands to two familiar dramatic tropes: arranged marriages and angry fathers. But it feels lazy and a bit dull in 2013. The mish-mash of accents delivered by the actors doesn't help, the lack of ambition even less so.</p><p>One radio show profiling another radio show should be too meta a concept to really work, but Judith Kampfner pulled it off for <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rv0m0/Archive_on_4_Radiolab/\" title=\"Archive on 4s look at Radiolab\"><strong>Archive on&nbsp;4's look at Radiolab</strong></a> last weekend, offering a solid primer on the cult US phenomenon broadcast on 300 American radio stations and downloaded as a podcast by 2 million listeners each week. What makes it so successful, asked Kampfner, and why are fellow broadcasters so in awe of it? Even Ira Glass, presenter of <a href=\"http://www.thisamericanlife.org/\" title=\"This American Life\"><strong>This American Life</strong></a>, was floored. \"They heard what we were doing and took the whole thing further,\" he cheerfully admitted. \"The aesthetic is much more evolved … it's more interactive, dynamic and fun.\" High praise.</p><p>Meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/\" title=\"Radiolab\"><strong>Radiolab</strong></a> skipped its usual format (esoteric science chat and brainy soundscapes) for a special reading by actor Liev Schrieber. What if the moon was just a jump away, asked hosts Jad Abumrad and Robert Krulwich. The answer was delivered in Italo Calvino's The Distance of the Moon, a trippy short story from the 60s, beautifully rendered in Schrieber's deep timbre.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/afghanistan\">Afghanistan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/nosheen-iqbal\">Nosheen Iqbal</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/everyday-story-of-afghan-folk" (20848 56679) old 5 nil nil ((title nil "A week in radio: An Afghan story") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/everyday-story-of-afghan-folk") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/54708?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aeveryday-story-of-afghan-folk%3A1896020&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Afghanistan+%28News%29%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media&c6=Nosheen+Iqbal&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1896020&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Radio+review+%28G2+series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=An+Everyday+Story+of+Afghan+Folk%3B+Archive+on+4%3A+radio+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FAfghanistan\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">This play adapted from an Afghani soap opera would have been great in the 80s, but sounds a bit dull now<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\">An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00hg8dq\" title=\"Archive on 4\">Archive on 4</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/blogs/radiolab-blog/2013/apr/16/distance-of-moon/\" title=\"Radiolab\">Radiolab</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01k2db9\" title=\"An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk\"><strong>An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk</strong></a> returned for a second series on Radio&nbsp;4 this week, filling in the daily 15 minute drama slot with an imagined take on village life on the Af-Pak border. \"Tell your father you want to marry Shireen, addict or not!\" yelled Meera Syal, playing the Pashtun wife of a poor farmer in her stock elderly Indian biddy accent, scolding a daughter with ideas above her station. The idea being education, the station being the school that pompous village leader Akbar Khan is secretly intent on blowing up.</p><p>This sort of thing would have been wonderful in the 80s – a worthy play adapted from an actual Afghani soap opera (<a href=\"http://www.pactradio.com/en/drama/news/bbc-radio-4-to-broadcast-a-season-of-the-pulay-poray-drama.php\" title=\"Pulay Poray\">Pulay Poray</a> in this case), boiling down the nuances of life and culture on the borderlands to two familiar dramatic tropes: arranged marriages and angry fathers. But it feels lazy and a bit dull in 2013. The mish-mash of accents delivered by the actors doesn't help, the lack of ambition even less so.</p><p>One radio show profiling another radio show should be too meta a concept to really work, but Judith Kampfner pulled it off for <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rv0m0/Archive_on_4_Radiolab/\" title=\"Archive on 4s look at Radiolab\"><strong>Archive on&nbsp;4's look at Radiolab</strong></a> last weekend, offering a solid primer on the cult US phenomenon broadcast on 300 American radio stations and downloaded as a podcast by 2 million listeners each week. What makes it so successful, asked Kampfner, and why are fellow broadcasters so in awe of it? Even Ira Glass, presenter of <a href=\"http://www.thisamericanlife.org/\" title=\"This American Life\"><strong>This American Life</strong></a>, was floored. \"They heard what we were doing and took the whole thing further,\" he cheerfully admitted. \"The aesthetic is much more evolved … it's more interactive, dynamic and fun.\" High praise.</p><p>Meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.radiolab.org/\" title=\"Radiolab\"><strong>Radiolab</strong></a> skipped its usual format (esoteric science chat and brainy soundscapes) for a special reading by actor Liev Schrieber. What if the moon was just a jump away, asked hosts Jad Abumrad and Robert Krulwich. The answer was delivered in Italo Calvino's The Distance of the Moon, a trippy short story from the 60s, beautifully rendered in Schrieber's deep timbre.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/afghanistan\">Afghanistan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/nosheen-iqbal\">Nosheen Iqbal</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Afghanistan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 06:00:07 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/everyday-story-of-afghan-folk") (dc:creator nil "Nosheen Iqbal") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T06:00:07Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407452778") (media:keywords nil "Afghanistan, Radio, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366298613914/Meera-Syal-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Tristram Kenton/Tristram Kenton") (media:description nil "Meera Syal, star of An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk, as she appeared in Much Ado About Nothing for the RSC. Photograph: Tristram Kenton")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366298621995/Meera-Syal-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Tristram Kenton/Tristram Kenton") (media:description nil "Meera Syal, star of An Everyday Story of Afghan Folk, as she appeared in Much Ado About Nothing for the RSC. Photograph: Tristram Kenton")))) ("Spartacus: box set review" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/82184?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aspartacus-box-set-review%3A1895903&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Spartacus+%28TV+programme%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Phelim+O%27Neill&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+03%3A00&c8=1895903&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CReview&c13=Your+next+box+set+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Spartacus%3A+box+set+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FSpartacus\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">There's so much more to Spartacus than the sex, blood and gore – but nevertheless there is a great deal of sex, blood and gore ...</p><p>It's commonly thought that this <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ptX_pjz5s2k\" title=\"visceral, swaggering show\">visceral, swaggering show</a> fumbled its start, presenting opening episodes so full of sex and violence that many (mostly the sort of killjoys who find make-believe sex and violence automatically unpalatable) were unable to see anything else, or accept the context in which such strong elements were presented. Looking back on those introductory episodes now the show has finished on Sky 1, they are really not that different from what followed; Spartacus started with <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q94bZ0NyJEg\" title=\"everything turned up to 11\">everything turned up to 11</a> and never flagged. The always entertaining dialogue was as stylised as the action: \"You scale a mountain of ifs and I would add to its peak.\" It was up to you to get used to it; if you did, you'd be hooked on a show that constantly delivered the goods.</p><p>It also tragically lost its Spartacus when cancer took lead <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VtPfga7VitA\" title=\"Andy Whitfield\">Andy Whitfield</a>. While he was ill, after season one (Blood and Sand), a short prequel series (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ou2TvLK9jzg\" title=\"Gods of the Arena\">Gods of the Arena</a>) kept the show going and expanded the back-story of the many supporting characters, turning the show into more of an ensemble piece. John Hannah's furiously ambitious <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GW2sNb1cd-w\" title=\"Batiatus\">Batiatus</a>, Lucy Lawless as his equally <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUEj3mvrLbU\" title=\"ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennetts Crixus the undefeated Gaul\">ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennett's Crixus the undefeated Gaul</a>, Dustin Clare's swaggering gladiator <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s71sZrOlJHk\" title=\"Gannicus\">Gannicus</a>, Nick Tarabay's stupendously duplicitous <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AKMI2f1xkA0\" title=\"Ashur\">Ashur</a>: the show was full of memorable characters that it had no worries about killing off (it's no surprise that almost everyone dies, that's the kind of spoiler that is usually taught in schools).</p><p>When Whitfield's replacement, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJdh6yJBJpQ\" title=\"Liam McIntyre\">Liam McIntyre</a>, joined the show for series three, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tNdutDDCUQU\" title=\"Vengeance\">Vengeance</a>, and the final <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\" title=\"War of the Damned\">War of the Damned</a>, his Spartacus was suitably more sullen, less cocky, still as unrelentingly hateful of the Romans as before, but bearing the weight of a man who was fighting not just for revenge of his murdered wife, but for freedom for all. Knowing how it ends doesn't diminish its power; rather it comes loaded with a crushing inevitability. With no wasted episodes, Spartacus never drags its sandalled feet.</p><p>It turned out to be an extremely tightly plotted affair, the storytelling as flab-free as the athletic cast, full of twists, surprises, and such never-before-seen-on-TV things as a bridge made of corpses and a gay couple (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2J6p5lCFrA\" title=\"Agron and Nasir\">Agron and Nasir</a>, dubbed Nagron by fans) who make it to the end without anyone commenting on their sexuality. You get blood and gore but so much more.</p><p><br />Reading this on a mobile? <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\">Click here to view video</a></p><p>The levels of violence are insanely high; the screen is surreally sprayed with gore, and the fight choreography surpasses movie quality. But the violence is not used just to look cool – see, for instance, the episode Decimation, where we learn the proper use of the word, as 10% of a Roman squad are harrowingly beaten to death. It's inventive too: just when you think you've seen every combination of hacking and slashing a body apart, along comes the scene where Spartacus slices the entire front of someone's head off. That's variety for you.</p><p>While it wouldn't have been made were it not for the success of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol67qo3WhJk\" title=\"Gladiator\">Gladiator</a> and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDiUG52ZyHQ\" title=\"300\">300</a>, Spartacus ended up outclassing those high-grossing movies in almost every department, save popularity. The virtue of the long-form storytelling (39 episodes in all) is that even when a minor character dies it has the impact of losing, if not an old friend, then at least a long-term acquaintance. And the finale must be one of the most emotionally violent ever televised, with a message, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SYRGF0GWTD4\" title=\"delivered in Spartacuss pre-battle speech\">delivered in Spartacus's pre-battle speech</a>, that rings through the ages as he fights for those \"forced to toil and suffer while those in coin and position see their fortunes grow beyond need or purpose.\" 'Twas ever thus.</p><p>The Starz Channel's Spartacus is one of the TV highpoints of recent years – or at least it would be considered so, had it gathered more viewers. It may yet be regarded as such, for if there was ever a show that benefited from the boxset format, it's Spartacus. Watch a few episodes. If you don't like it then watch a couple more, because when it takes, you'll be gripped and put through the wringer.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/spartacus\">Spartacus</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/phelimoneill\">Phelim O'Neill</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review" (20847 64610) old 7 nil nil ((title nil "Spartacus: box set review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/82184?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aspartacus-box-set-review%3A1895903&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Spartacus+%28TV+programme%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Phelim+O%27Neill&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+03%3A00&c8=1895903&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CReview&c13=Your+next+box+set+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Spartacus%3A+box+set+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FSpartacus\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">There's so much more to Spartacus than the sex, blood and gore – but nevertheless there is a great deal of sex, blood and gore ...</p><p>It's commonly thought that this <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ptX_pjz5s2k\" title=\"visceral, swaggering show\">visceral, swaggering show</a> fumbled its start, presenting opening episodes so full of sex and violence that many (mostly the sort of killjoys who find make-believe sex and violence automatically unpalatable) were unable to see anything else, or accept the context in which such strong elements were presented. Looking back on those introductory episodes now the show has finished on Sky 1, they are really not that different from what followed; Spartacus started with <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q94bZ0NyJEg\" title=\"everything turned up to 11\">everything turned up to 11</a> and never flagged. The always entertaining dialogue was as stylised as the action: \"You scale a mountain of ifs and I would add to its peak.\" It was up to you to get used to it; if you did, you'd be hooked on a show that constantly delivered the goods.</p><p>It also tragically lost its Spartacus when cancer took lead <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VtPfga7VitA\" title=\"Andy Whitfield\">Andy Whitfield</a>. While he was ill, after season one (Blood and Sand), a short prequel series (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ou2TvLK9jzg\" title=\"Gods of the Arena\">Gods of the Arena</a>) kept the show going and expanded the back-story of the many supporting characters, turning the show into more of an ensemble piece. John Hannah's furiously ambitious <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GW2sNb1cd-w\" title=\"Batiatus\">Batiatus</a>, Lucy Lawless as his equally <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUEj3mvrLbU\" title=\"ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennetts Crixus the undefeated Gaul\">ruthless wife Lucretia, Manu Bennett's Crixus the undefeated Gaul</a>, Dustin Clare's swaggering gladiator <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s71sZrOlJHk\" title=\"Gannicus\">Gannicus</a>, Nick Tarabay's stupendously duplicitous <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AKMI2f1xkA0\" title=\"Ashur\">Ashur</a>: the show was full of memorable characters that it had no worries about killing off (it's no surprise that almost everyone dies, that's the kind of spoiler that is usually taught in schools).</p><p>When Whitfield's replacement, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJdh6yJBJpQ\" title=\"Liam McIntyre\">Liam McIntyre</a>, joined the show for series three, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tNdutDDCUQU\" title=\"Vengeance\">Vengeance</a>, and the final <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\" title=\"War of the Damned\">War of the Damned</a>, his Spartacus was suitably more sullen, less cocky, still as unrelentingly hateful of the Romans as before, but bearing the weight of a man who was fighting not just for revenge of his murdered wife, but for freedom for all. Knowing how it ends doesn't diminish its power; rather it comes loaded with a crushing inevitability. With no wasted episodes, Spartacus never drags its sandalled feet.</p><p>It turned out to be an extremely tightly plotted affair, the storytelling as flab-free as the athletic cast, full of twists, surprises, and such never-before-seen-on-TV things as a bridge made of corpses and a gay couple (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2J6p5lCFrA\" title=\"Agron and Nasir\">Agron and Nasir</a>, dubbed Nagron by fans) who make it to the end without anyone commenting on their sexuality. You get blood and gore but so much more.</p><p><br />Reading this on a mobile? <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qXoC-DykyM\">Click here to view video</a></p><p>The levels of violence are insanely high; the screen is surreally sprayed with gore, and the fight choreography surpasses movie quality. But the violence is not used just to look cool – see, for instance, the episode Decimation, where we learn the proper use of the word, as 10% of a Roman squad are harrowingly beaten to death. It's inventive too: just when you think you've seen every combination of hacking and slashing a body apart, along comes the scene where Spartacus slices the entire front of someone's head off. That's variety for you.</p><p>While it wouldn't have been made were it not for the success of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol67qo3WhJk\" title=\"Gladiator\">Gladiator</a> and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDiUG52ZyHQ\" title=\"300\">300</a>, Spartacus ended up outclassing those high-grossing movies in almost every department, save popularity. The virtue of the long-form storytelling (39 episodes in all) is that even when a minor character dies it has the impact of losing, if not an old friend, then at least a long-term acquaintance. And the finale must be one of the most emotionally violent ever televised, with a message, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SYRGF0GWTD4\" title=\"delivered in Spartacuss pre-battle speech\">delivered in Spartacus's pre-battle speech</a>, that rings through the ages as he fights for those \"forced to toil and suffer while those in coin and position see their fortunes grow beyond need or purpose.\" 'Twas ever thus.</p><p>The Starz Channel's Spartacus is one of the TV highpoints of recent years – or at least it would be considered so, had it gathered more viewers. It may yet be regarded as such, for if there was ever a show that benefited from the boxset format, it's Spartacus. Watch a few episodes. If you don't like it then watch a couple more, because when it takes, you'll be gripped and put through the wringer.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/spartacus\">Spartacus</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/phelimoneill\">Phelim O'Neill</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Spartacus") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 14:00:02 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review") (dc:creator nil "Phelim O'Neill") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T23:06:13Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407442691") (media:keywords nil "Spartacus, Historical drama, Television, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290155216/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290161321/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC")))) ("The return of The Fried Chicken Shop" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/33942?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areturn-of-fried-chicken-shop%3A1895793&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CFast+food+%28life+and+style%29%2CFood+and+drink++%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFood+and+Drink&c6=Stuart+Heritage&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+01%3A10&c8=1895793&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+return+of+The+Fried+Chicken+Shop&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The highly entertaining look at life in a London takeaway is coming back to Channel 4 for three new episodes. If they are as good as the first documentary, we are in for a treat</p><p>In February, Channel 4 aired <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-fried-chicken-shop-life-in-a-day\" title=\"\">The Fried Chicken Shop</a>, a one-off documentary set in a London fried chicken shop. Using the same fixed-rig setup that the channel loves to return to again and again, The Fried Chicken Shop took a week's worth of footage from Clapham's Roosters Spot eatery and distilled it into a tightly packed hour of entertainment. And it was much more fun than it had any right to be.</p><p></p><p>This week, Channel 4 announced that The Fried Chicken Shop is to return for three episodes that will repeat and expand on the premise of the original. We will still see the Roosters Spot staff grind out one impossibly long shift after another. We will still see Clapham's finest slumped over the counter at chucking-out time, manfully attempting to order a Mega Mix chicken burger with their last remaining molecule of dignity intact. But this time, we are promised, we will also get to follow some of the takeaway customers home. This new addition will almost certainly contain the most exciting footage of a lonely man sitting on a carpet in a bedsit and silently eating chips at 2am that British television has ever seen.</p><p></p><p>The beauty of The Fried Chicken Shop is its universality. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/24-hours-in-ae\" title=\"\">24 Hours in A&E</a> and feel admiration for the medical staff and their ability to maintain composure under extraordinary pressure. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-hotel\" title=\"\">The Hotel</a> and wonder why any of the guests agreed to let cameras into their rooms. But to watch The Fried Chicken Shop is to recognise a part of yourself.</p><p></p><p>Plenty of us, at one point or another, have bought fast food while drunk. Many of us will have done so without a second thought for the staff behind the counter. What The Fried Chicken Shop did so well was to make it clear how awful we probably are when we do this.  Judging by the show, the staff of Roosters Spot have put up with it all: aggressive drunks; attention-seeking drunks; people pretending to be disabled; drug dealers handing out business cards; and social media hipster dullards, who function as an argument for sawing a circle around the edge of London and letting it drop into the sea.</p><p></p><p>Watching the staff remain as good-natured and professional as they were in the face of such soul-sapping arsery was a joy. It was as heartwarming as anything else I have seen on television this year. And although it had the potential to lapse into the uncomfortably sneery classism that Channel 4's Gypsy programmes sometimes revel in, The Fried Chicken Shop staunchly refused to judge anyone. It didn't have a point to make, or an issue to force home, other than the awkward \"Wow, don't people eat a lot of chicken these days?\" message tacked on to the start. It was happy enough just to show us the chicken shop and let us reach our own conclusions. The first episode was magnificent. I can't wait to hang out there again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/fast-food\">Fast food</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink\">Food & drink</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=