sabled; drug dealers handing out business cards; and social media hipster dullards, who function as an argument for sawing a circle around the edge of London and letting it drop into the sea.</p><p></p><p>Watching the staff remain as good-natured and professional as they were in the face of such soul-sapping arsery was a joy. It was as heartwarming as anything else I have seen on television this year. And although it had the potential to lapse into the uncomfortably sneery classism that Channel 4's Gypsy programmes sometimes revel in, The Fried Chicken Shop staunchly refused to judge anyone. It didn't have a point to make, or an issue to force home, other than the awkward \"Wow, don't people eat a lot of chicken these days?\" message tacked on to the start. It was happy enough just to show us the chicken shop and let us reach our own conclusions. The first episode was magnificent. I can't wait to hang out there again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/fast-food\">Fast food</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink\">Food & drink</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stuart-heritage\">Stuart Heritage</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Documentary") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Factual TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Fast food") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Food & drink") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 12:10:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop") (dc:creator nil "Stuart Heritage") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T12:10:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407435148") (media:keywords nil "Television, Television & radio, Documentary, Factual TV, Fast food, Food & drink, Life and style") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284559725/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284566906/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes.")))) ("Why is EastEnders so bad?" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/26566?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Awhy-is-eastenders-so-bad%3A1895696&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=EastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Television+Media%2CTV&c6=Homa+Khaleeli&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+11%3A27&c8=1895696&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Why+is+EastEnders+so+bad%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FEastEnders\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The soap's ratings have been sliding for more than a year – and a host of major characters have quit the square. What can it do to win back disgruntled fans?</p><p>There is a problem on the Square. Sure, there have been the usual tear-stained wedding dramas, squalling rows in the Queen Vic and near-incestuous couplings, but something is wrong: E20 has lost its edge. <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-facing-ratings-crisis-angry-1771100\" title=\"\">Ratings have been on the slide for more than a year</a>, while forums have been filling up with disgruntled fans. To put it like a Walford local: wossgaoinon?</p><p>Well, for a start, there are the recycled storylines. It's been a staggering 20 years since the angry baby that is Phil Mitchell first seduced his brother's breathy wife Sharon. Now, like a market-stall knockoff of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2310171/EastEnders-Phil-Mitchell-finally-gets-girl-Sharon-Rickman-succumbs-brutish-charms.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">they are at it again for a third time</a>. It's a plot so lacking in excitement that on Monday night, the cliffhanger ending was Sharon's six-year-old son (complete with Ann Widdecombe haircut) threatening to run away from home.</p><p>Stuck in a similarly boring rut are Max and Tanya, who have also been splitting up and getting back together on a loop since they first arrived in Walford, the London borough where marriages go to die. After several affairs, attempted murders and short-lived relationships with other people, Max has left Tanya once more – this time for Kirsty, whose larger-than-life lips, eyelashes and hair extensions have been stuck on in place of a personality. But inevitably Max is yet again pining after Tanya – a situation so predictable even the couple's children merely roll their eyes in response.</p><p>On top of this there are the non-plots – actual screen time was devoted to discovering who had stolen Dot's cold cuts from the fridge. And then there are the really unbelievable ones. Such as Masood, the square's nicest father figure, dating 19-year-old Ayesha, before the writers shamefacedly let it fizzle out. To cheer us up,  they've since put together attractive Denise and slimy egomaniac Ian Beale as the square's supposedly hilarious odd couple. But seeing as the soap operates a strict looks-blind policy to casting – with Phil Mitchell and Max as the square studs while Ray has been confined to the Fox sisters – it's hardly the most shocking of hookups.</p><p>Despite a cull of characters last year (I am still in mourning for the loss of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2248900/Nina-Wadia-quits-EastEnders-years-playing-Zainab-Masood.html\" title=\"\">Zainab Masood</a>), Eastenders still has some great ones – Kim is hilarious, Shirley does tough vulnerability brilliantly, and Kat and Alfie still have an impressive amount of chemistry. But instead of giving them some depth and storylines to progress with, there has been an emphasis on bringing back old favourites to bring back some sparks. When in truth, we don't want the same old faces but some new plotlines to put the drama back in to the doof doof endings.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/homa-khaleeli\">Homa Khaleeli</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad" (20847 51847) old 2 nil nil ((title nil "Why is EastEnders so bad?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/26566?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Awhy-is-eastenders-so-bad%3A1895696&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=EastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Television+Media%2CTV&c6=Homa+Khaleeli&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+11%3A27&c8=1895696&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Why+is+EastEnders+so+bad%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FEastEnders\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The soap's ratings have been sliding for more than a year – and a host of major characters have quit the square. What can it do to win back disgruntled fans?</p><p>There is a problem on the Square. Sure, there have been the usual tear-stained wedding dramas, squalling rows in the Queen Vic and near-incestuous couplings, but something is wrong: E20 has lost its edge. <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-facing-ratings-crisis-angry-1771100\" title=\"\">Ratings have been on the slide for more than a year</a>, while forums have been filling up with disgruntled fans. To put it like a Walford local: wossgaoinon?</p><p>Well, for a start, there are the recycled storylines. It's been a staggering 20 years since the angry baby that is Phil Mitchell first seduced his brother's breathy wife Sharon. Now, like a market-stall knockoff of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2310171/EastEnders-Phil-Mitchell-finally-gets-girl-Sharon-Rickman-succumbs-brutish-charms.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">they are at it again for a third time</a>. It's a plot so lacking in excitement that on Monday night, the cliffhanger ending was Sharon's six-year-old son (complete with Ann Widdecombe haircut) threatening to run away from home.</p><p>Stuck in a similarly boring rut are Max and Tanya, who have also been splitting up and getting back together on a loop since they first arrived in Walford, the London borough where marriages go to die. After several affairs, attempted murders and short-lived relationships with other people, Max has left Tanya once more – this time for Kirsty, whose larger-than-life lips, eyelashes and hair extensions have been stuck on in place of a personality. But inevitably Max is yet again pining after Tanya – a situation so predictable even the couple's children merely roll their eyes in response.</p><p>On top of this there are the non-plots – actual screen time was devoted to discovering who had stolen Dot's cold cuts from the fridge. And then there are the really unbelievable ones. Such as Masood, the square's nicest father figure, dating 19-year-old Ayesha, before the writers shamefacedly let it fizzle out. To cheer us up,  they've since put together attractive Denise and slimy egomaniac Ian Beale as the square's supposedly hilarious odd couple. But seeing as the soap operates a strict looks-blind policy to casting – with Phil Mitchell and Max as the square studs while Ray has been confined to the Fox sisters – it's hardly the most shocking of hookups.</p><p>Despite a cull of characters last year (I am still in mourning for the loss of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2248900/Nina-Wadia-quits-EastEnders-years-playing-Zainab-Masood.html\" title=\"\">Zainab Masood</a>), Eastenders still has some great ones – Kim is hilarious, Shirley does tough vulnerability brilliantly, and Kat and Alfie still have an impressive amount of chemistry. But instead of giving them some depth and storylines to progress with, there has been an emphasis on bringing back old favourites to bring back some sparks. When in truth, we don't want the same old faces but some new plotlines to put the drama back in to the doof doof endings.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/homa-khaleeli\">Homa Khaleeli</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "EastEnders") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Soap opera") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 10:27:19 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (dc:creator nil "Homa Khaleeli") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T11:18:56Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407427102") (media:keywords nil "EastEnders, Television, Drama, Soap opera") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279202222/EastEnders---third-time-l-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279210312/EastEnders---third-time-l-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron")))) ("The Sea Devils: Doctor Who classic episode #5" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/24956?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode%3A1894855&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Doctor+Who+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CScience+fiction+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Dan+Martin&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+12%3A23&c8=1894855&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=The+best+Doctor+Who+episodes+of+all+time&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+Sea+Devils%3A+Doctor+Who+classic+episode+%235&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDoctor+Who\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Doctor is finally in colour, stranded on Earth – and up against his arch enemy, in the form of Roger Delgado's Master</p><h2>The Sea Devils: episode three (11 March 1972)</h2><p><em>The One Where …</em> Earth's original inhabitants rise from the sea, and the Master gets into The Clangers</p><p><em>SPOILER ALERT: We'll be discussing some of the Doctor Who adventures broadcast over the last 50 years. In this blog, we're looking at part three of The Sea Devils. It contains spoilers both about the specific episode and the story as a whole.</em></p><p>Two years earlier, the Silurians had proved a triumph, the story of a dormant pre-human race rising to reclaim the planet brought a spectrum of grey to Who. Unwilling to broker a deal to share the planet, the Brigadier had ordered their destruction. It was ripe for a sequel, and so producers decided to repurpose the story, this time with a marine setting. The Sea Devils doesn't quite have the bleak undercurrents of its predecessor but the scale and execution of this bring it out on top for me.</p><p>The co-operation of the navy meant the episode could live up to its blockbusting ambitions, and it's a a technical triumph packed with vintage moments: speedboats, swordfights, reversing-the-polarity-of-the-neutron flow and the Master watching The Clangers from his island prison. Oh yes, the Master; Roger Delgado is on electrifying form here.</p><p>This was at the height of the Doctor's Earth-bound adventures, as the Timelords exiled him to our world just as the show got colour. There was a lot of talk of The Bells of Saint John channelling James Bond a few weeks back, but Jon Pertwee's action-packed era was a closer cousin to 007 in the Roger Moore days. Unit – the military organisation for whom the Doctor is working as scientific advisor – doesn't feature here, but its buttoned-up British pomp is all over this navy-themed tale.</p><p>Of an impressive guest cast, most memorable is Martin Boddey as gluttonous minister Walker, ordering missile strikes in between mouthfuls of cake. The Sea Devils goes down as one of the most memorable Pertwee stories of all, and it's tricky to pick a best episode when the reach is so cinematic. So how about that cliffhanger to episode three, with that first monster emerging from the sea, surely one of the most memorable sequences in all of Who?</p><h2>Life aboard the Tardis </h2><p>The Timelords had exiled the Doctor to Earth, so there was no gallivanting round space and time in the third Doctor's early years. But there was a terrific ensemble in the Unit family, with a special favourite in Katy Manning as Jo Grant, one of the most beloved companions of all. Brought in to replace scientist Liz Shaw, whom producers had decided was a little too accomplished, Grant reversed the template of companions asking lots of questions. And she went round making an awful lot of tea without even being asked. But what the junior civilian operative for the UN lacked in progression, she more than made up for in fierce loyalty; the relationship between her and Pertwee's Doctor is one of the most tender in the show's history, and Katy Manning herself has gone on to be one of Who's proudest ambassadors. </p><h2>Behind the sofa </h2><p>The turtle-like\" sea devils\" (though never actually named as such) go down as a design classic, their menace only slightly undercut by the hospital fatigues they appear to be wearing. And that Silurian set-up, that someone was here before us is, as Steven Moffat noted in recent years, a \"movie franchise idea\". But The Sea Devils isn't in itself a scary story. And like the any Master story, the show is stolen by Roger Delgado's masterclass in polite psychopathy, returning after a year off. After being captured in The Daemons, he was imprisoned, and claiming to be reformed. But as the unfortunates at the prison soon discover, you can't keep a bad Timelord down; he's soon manipulating the governer and taking people down with his Jedi mind tricks.</p><h2>Behind the scenes </h2><p>The hovercraft sequence is also responsible for one of the fruitier production anecdotes. As Katy Manning recalls on the DVD extras, the vessel tipped over slightly to one side, leading to a \"nautical rugby scrum\". As she said with a cackle: \"It was a pretty exciting moment actually. I had something like 24 sailors on top of me, now there's a memory! I said to them afterwards: 'I'm going to have to marry all of you; we've just been too close,' and Jon was actually deeply concerned, he was not happy about that moment.\" (The production proved even more challenging for Delgado, who couldn't swim.)</p><h2>Fragments</h2><p>• \"Reverse the polarity of the neutron flow\", might be the third Doctor's most famous catchphrase, but he actually only ever used it twice: here, and in his anniversary comeback in The Five Doctors.</p><p>• I tweeted Manning at the weekend to tell her I was watching her in The Sea Devils. She replied:</p><p>I'm not quite sure what that means.</p><p>• Another iconic sequence here is the sight of what is quite clearly a burly stunt guy's bottom standing in for Manning. The man in question was named Stuart Fell.</p><p>• The Doctor, we learn, was a close personal friend of Horatio Nelson.</p><p>• Would they really have kept fencing swords right next to the prison cell of a dangerous criminal?</p><h2>Further reading </h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/seadevils/detail.shtml\" title=\"\">The official BBC page, with the usual list of amusing goofs.</a></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.radiotimes.com/blog/2009-12-14/doctor-who-the-sea-devils\" title=\"\">A Radio Times re-appraisal from a few years ago</a>.</p><p>• <a href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20080629134959/http://www.gallifreyone.com/review.php?id=3l\" title=\"\">And here's a review from those sensible people at Outpost Gallifrey</a></p><h2>Next time </h2><p>The one with the Maggots! Yes, we really are doing The Green Death, after the wrong listing last time. Sorry about that.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/doctor-who\">Doctor Who</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/science-fiction\">Science fiction</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/danmartin\">Dan Martin</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/the-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode" (20846 34324) old 9 nil nil ((title nil "The Sea Devils: Doctor Who classic episode #5") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/the-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/24956?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode%3A1894855&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Doctor+Who+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CScience+fiction+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Dan+Martin&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+12%3A23&c8=1894855&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=The+best+Doctor+Who+episodes+of+all+time&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+Sea+Devils%3A+Doctor+Who+classic+episode+%235&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDoctor+Who\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Doctor is finally in colour, stranded on Earth – and up against his arch enemy, in the form of Roger Delgado's Master</p><h2>The Sea Devils: episode three (11 March 1972)</h2><p><em>The One Where …</em> Earth's original inhabitants rise from the sea, and the Master gets into The Clangers</p><p><em>SPOILER ALERT: We'll be discussing some of the Doctor Who adventures broadcast over the last 50 years. In this blog, we're looking at part three of The Sea Devils. It contains spoilers both about the specific episode and the story as a whole.</em></p><p>Two years earlier, the Silurians had proved a triumph, the story of a dormant pre-human race rising to reclaim the planet brought a spectrum of grey to Who. Unwilling to broker a deal to share the planet, the Brigadier had ordered their destruction. It was ripe for a sequel, and so producers decided to repurpose the story, this time with a marine setting. The Sea Devils doesn't quite have the bleak undercurrents of its predecessor but the scale and execution of this bring it out on top for me.</p><p>The co-operation of the navy meant the episode could live up to its blockbusting ambitions, and it's a a technical triumph packed with vintage moments: speedboats, swordfights, reversing-the-polarity-of-the-neutron flow and the Master watching The Clangers from his island prison. Oh yes, the Master; Roger Delgado is on electrifying form here.</p><p>This was at the height of the Doctor's Earth-bound adventures, as the Timelords exiled him to our world just as the show got colour. There was a lot of talk of The Bells of Saint John channelling James Bond a few weeks back, but Jon Pertwee's action-packed era was a closer cousin to 007 in the Roger Moore days. Unit – the military organisation for whom the Doctor is working as scientific advisor – doesn't feature here, but its buttoned-up British pomp is all over this navy-themed tale.</p><p>Of an impressive guest cast, most memorable is Martin Boddey as gluttonous minister Walker, ordering missile strikes in between mouthfuls of cake. The Sea Devils goes down as one of the most memorable Pertwee stories of all, and it's tricky to pick a best episode when the reach is so cinematic. So how about that cliffhanger to episode three, with that first monster emerging from the sea, surely one of the most memorable sequences in all of Who?</p><h2>Life aboard the Tardis </h2><p>The Timelords had exiled the Doctor to Earth, so there was no gallivanting round space and time in the third Doctor's early years. But there was a terrific ensemble in the Unit family, with a special favourite in Katy Manning as Jo Grant, one of the most beloved companions of all. Brought in to replace scientist Liz Shaw, whom producers had decided was a little too accomplished, Grant reversed the template of companions asking lots of questions. And she went round making an awful lot of tea without even being asked. But what the junior civilian operative for the UN lacked in progression, she more than made up for in fierce loyalty; the relationship between her and Pertwee's Doctor is one of the most tender in the show's history, and Katy Manning herself has gone on to be one of Who's proudest ambassadors. </p><h2>Behind the sofa </h2><p>The turtle-like\" sea devils\" (though never actually named as such) go down as a design classic, their menace only slightly undercut by the hospital fatigues they appear to be wearing. And that Silurian set-up, that someone was here before us is, as Steven Moffat noted in recent years, a \"movie franchise idea\". But The Sea Devils isn't in itself a scary story. And like the any Master story, the show is stolen by Roger Delgado's masterclass in polite psychopathy, returning after a year off. After being captured in The Daemons, he was imprisoned, and claiming to be reformed. But as the unfortunates at the prison soon discover, you can't keep a bad Timelord down; he's soon manipulating the governer and taking people down with his Jedi mind tricks.</p><h2>Behind the scenes </h2><p>The hovercraft sequence is also responsible for one of the fruitier production anecdotes. As Katy Manning recalls on the DVD extras, the vessel tipped over slightly to one side, leading to a \"nautical rugby scrum\". As she said with a cackle: \"It was a pretty exciting moment actually. I had something like 24 sailors on top of me, now there's a memory! I said to them afterwards: 'I'm going to have to marry all of you; we've just been too close,' and Jon was actually deeply concerned, he was not happy about that moment.\" (The production proved even more challenging for Delgado, who couldn't swim.)</p><h2>Fragments</h2><p>• \"Reverse the polarity of the neutron flow\", might be the third Doctor's most famous catchphrase, but he actually only ever used it twice: here, and in his anniversary comeback in The Five Doctors.</p><p>• I tweeted Manning at the weekend to tell her I was watching her in The Sea Devils. She replied:</p><p>I'm not quite sure what that means.</p><p>• Another iconic sequence here is the sight of what is quite clearly a burly stunt guy's bottom standing in for Manning. The man in question was named Stuart Fell.</p><p>• The Doctor, we learn, was a close personal friend of Horatio Nelson.</p><p>• Would they really have kept fencing swords right next to the prison cell of a dangerous criminal?</p><h2>Further reading </h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/seadevils/detail.shtml\" title=\"\">The official BBC page, with the usual list of amusing goofs.</a></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.radiotimes.com/blog/2009-12-14/doctor-who-the-sea-devils\" title=\"\">A Radio Times re-appraisal from a few years ago</a>.</p><p>• <a href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20080629134959/http://www.gallifreyone.com/review.php?id=3l\" title=\"\">And here's a review from those sensible people at Outpost Gallifrey</a></p><h2>Next time </h2><p>The one with the Maggots! Yes, we really are doing The Green Death, after the wrong listing last time. Sorry about that.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/doctor-who\">Doctor Who</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/science-fiction\">Science fiction</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/danmartin\">Dan Martin</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Doctor Who") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Science fiction") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 11:23:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/the-sea-devils-doctor-who-classic-episode") (dc:creator nil "Dan Martin") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T11:30:17Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407309642") (media:keywords nil "Doctor Who, Science fiction, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/online/2013/4/17/1366191009306/The-Sea-Devils-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC") (media:description nil "The Sea Devils Photograph: BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/online/2013/4/17/1366191015018/The-Sea-Devils-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC") (media:description nil "The Doctor and a 'sea devil'. Photograph: BBC")))) ("Marc Maron: podcast turned TV star" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/45669?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amarc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv%3A1894826&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Comedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CPodcasting+%28Media%29%2CInternet%2CDigital+media%2CMedia%2CComedy+live+%28Stage%29%2CCulture&c5=Digital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTechnology+Gadgets%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Diane+Shipley&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+05%3A42&c8=1894826&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Marc+Maron+is+the+latest+comedy+star+to+go+from+podcast+to+TV+pilot&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FComedy\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The route from internet audio show to TV and publishing success is well trodden in the US, but why are so few British comics keen to follow suit?</p><p>Last week IFC (the network that produces Portlandia) released the trailer for <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OqVaAqOIpYA\" title=\"\">Maron</a>, comedian Marc Maron's semi-autobiographical sitcom, which premieres in May. Its creator/star also has a book of essays, called Attempting Normal, published at the end of this month. But just four years ago, by his own admission, Maron <a href=\"http://www.believermag.com/exclusives/? read=\"interview_maron\"\" title=\"\">\"had nothing going on\"</a>. Having made his name in the 90s alternative comedy scene, he had lost touch with his more famous peers, including Louis CK and Patton Oswalt. Twice-divorced and fired from his third radio hosting gig in four years, Maron moved from New York to LA with three cats and few prospects. The 49-year-old's current career revival is all thanks to his hugely popular podcast, WTF, a twice-weekly interview show where he has swapped laughs and neuroses with everyone from Sarah Silverman to Robin Williams.</p><p>Now he's following in the footsteps of Scott Aukerman, whose improv podcast Comedy Bang! Bang! was also adapted for television by IFC, and Chris Hardwick, creator of The Nerdist podcast. Not content with one TV show, Hardwick also fronts a post-Walking Dead discussion called Talking Dead, has filmed a pilot for Comedy Central and last month launched the first series of the Nerdist TV show for BBC America. While he gained notoriety presenting cheesy dating shows in the 90s, it took a podcast to give him credibility. And he's not the only one.</p><p>Aisha Tyler is probably best known for playing Ross's girlfriend Charlie on Friends, but her Girl on Guy podcast made a wider audience aware of her comedy roots. As a result, she was announced as the new host of Whose Line Is It Anyway? last month and <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Self-Inflicted-Wounds-Heartwarming-Tales-Humiliation/dp/0062223771/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1365974995&sr=8-1&keywords=self+inflicted+wounds\" title=\"\">has her own book coming out this summer</a>. Meanwhile, comedian Pete Holmes has parlayed the success of his podcast You Made It Weird into <a href=\"http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/02/26/pete-holmes-conan-obrien-late-night-show-tbs/\" title=\"\">an upcoming sketch show</a>. And although it wasn't true, <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-nbc-renews-carson-daly-alec-baldwin-rumors-20130410,0,453985.story\" title=\"\">a recent rumour</a> that 30 Rock actor Alec Baldwin would take over Carson Daly's late-night talkshow seemed plausible thanks to the interviewing prowess he has shown on his own podcast, <a href=\"http://www.wnyc.org/shows/heresthething/\" title=\"\">Here's the Thing</a>.</p><p>When podcasts started back in 2004, few people realised their career-boosting potential. Pioneers such as Jesse Thorn and Dan Klass made quality shows that attracted loyal audiences and media coverage. But when I fired up my first MP3 player in 2005, I listened to a lot of podcasts that featured unintended sound effects and prolonged drunken giggling fits. Their creators often described them as \"homemade radio shows\" and that was exactly how they sounded.</p><p>They have become considerably slicker since then. To be a comedian in the US without a podcast is increasingly to be an oddity. It may even be a liability. Podcasts are a becoming an easy way for TV networks to find fresh talent with an established following. The potential for them to be used as a springboard to writing, acting, and presenting jobs is huge.</p><p>But they haven't taken off in quite the same way in the UK. Here podcasts tend to be drawn from popular radio shows made by established media corporations (such as <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-danny-baker-show/id330285088\">Danny Baker's BBC podcast</a>) rather than original, independently produced content. One exception is The Ricky Gervais Show, which Channel 4 adapted into an animated series in 2010. But Gervais had established a career in entertainment long before he hit \"record\".</p><p>So why are up-and-coming comedians in the UK less interested in building a millions-strong audio audience than their US counterparts? Perhaps because we have a more thriving live scene – America has no real equivalent to the Edinburgh festival, and the comparative size of our countries means it's far easier for British comedians to build a following by touring. Or it may just be that we're a step behind. Either way, it's a shame.</p><p>Cheaper and easier to put together than a YouTube production (and marginally less likely to attract incendiary comments), podcasts can provide a low-risk, low-cost way to try out new material, and not just for comedians. Releasing chapters of his audiobooks as podcasts helped <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/01/books/01podb.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0\" title=\"\">Scott Sigler become a self-publishing superstar</a>. Perhaps it's time for writers and performers on this side of the Atlantic to take note – and pick up a mic.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/podcasting\">Podcasting</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/internet\">Internet</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/digital-media\">Digital media</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dianeshipley\">Diane Shipley</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/marc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv" (20845 32600) old 10 nil nil ((title nil "Marc Maron: podcast turned TV star") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/marc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/45669?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amarc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv%3A1894826&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Comedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CPodcasting+%28Media%29%2CInternet%2CDigital+media%2CMedia%2CComedy+live+%28Stage%29%2CCulture&c5=Digital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTechnology+Gadgets%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Diane+Shipley&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+05%3A42&c8=1894826&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Marc+Maron+is+the+latest+comedy+star+to+go+from+podcast+to+TV+pilot&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FComedy\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The route from internet audio show to TV and publishing success is well trodden in the US, but why are so few British comics keen to follow suit?</p><p>Last week IFC (the network that produces Portlandia) released the trailer for <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OqVaAqOIpYA\" title=\"\">Maron</a>, comedian Marc Maron's semi-autobiographical sitcom, which premieres in May. Its creator/star also has a book of essays, called Attempting Normal, published at the end of this month. But just four years ago, by his own admission, Maron <a href=\"http://www.believermag.com/exclusives/? read=\"interview_maron\"\" title=\"\">\"had nothing going on\"</a>. Having made his name in the 90s alternative comedy scene, he had lost touch with his more famous peers, including Louis CK and Patton Oswalt. Twice-divorced and fired from his third radio hosting gig in four years, Maron moved from New York to LA with three cats and few prospects. The 49-year-old's current career revival is all thanks to his hugely popular podcast, WTF, a twice-weekly interview show where he has swapped laughs and neuroses with everyone from Sarah Silverman to Robin Williams.</p><p>Now he's following in the footsteps of Scott Aukerman, whose improv podcast Comedy Bang! Bang! was also adapted for television by IFC, and Chris Hardwick, creator of The Nerdist podcast. Not content with one TV show, Hardwick also fronts a post-Walking Dead discussion called Talking Dead, has filmed a pilot for Comedy Central and last month launched the first series of the Nerdist TV show for BBC America. While he gained notoriety presenting cheesy dating shows in the 90s, it took a podcast to give him credibility. And he's not the only one.</p><p>Aisha Tyler is probably best known for playing Ross's girlfriend Charlie on Friends, but her Girl on Guy podcast made a wider audience aware of her comedy roots. As a result, she was announced as the new host of Whose Line Is It Anyway? last month and <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Self-Inflicted-Wounds-Heartwarming-Tales-Humiliation/dp/0062223771/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1365974995&sr=8-1&keywords=self+inflicted+wounds\" title=\"\">has her own book coming out this summer</a>. Meanwhile, comedian Pete Holmes has parlayed the success of his podcast You Made It Weird into <a href=\"http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/02/26/pete-holmes-conan-obrien-late-night-show-tbs/\" title=\"\">an upcoming sketch show</a>. And although it wasn't true, <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-nbc-renews-carson-daly-alec-baldwin-rumors-20130410,0,453985.story\" title=\"\">a recent rumour</a> that 30 Rock actor Alec Baldwin would take over Carson Daly's late-night talkshow seemed plausible thanks to the interviewing prowess he has shown on his own podcast, <a href=\"http://www.wnyc.org/shows/heresthething/\" title=\"\">Here's the Thing</a>.</p><p>When podcasts started back in 2004, few people realised their career-boosting potential. Pioneers such as Jesse Thorn and Dan Klass made quality shows that attracted loyal audiences and media coverage. But when I fired up my first MP3 player in 2005, I listened to a lot of podcasts that featured unintended sound effects and prolonged drunken giggling fits. Their creators often described them as \"homemade radio shows\" and that was exactly how they sounded.</p><p>They have become considerably slicker since then. To be a comedian in the US without a podcast is increasingly to be an oddity. It may even be a liability. Podcasts are a becoming an easy way for TV networks to find fresh talent with an established following. The potential for them to be used as a springboard to writing, acting, and presenting jobs is huge.</p><p>But they haven't taken off in quite the same way in the UK. Here podcasts tend to be drawn from popular radio shows made by established media corporations (such as <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/podcast/the-danny-baker-show/id330285088\">Danny Baker's BBC podcast</a>) rather than original, independently produced content. One exception is The Ricky Gervais Show, which Channel 4 adapted into an animated series in 2010. But Gervais had established a career in entertainment long before he hit \"record\".</p><p>So why are up-and-coming comedians in the UK less interested in building a millions-strong audio audience than their US counterparts? Perhaps because we have a more thriving live scene – America has no real equivalent to the Edinburgh festival, and the comparative size of our countries means it's far easier for British comedians to build a following by touring. Or it may just be that we're a step behind. Either way, it's a shame.</p><p>Cheaper and easier to put together than a YouTube production (and marginally less likely to attract incendiary comments), podcasts can provide a low-risk, low-cost way to try out new material, and not just for comedians. Releasing chapters of his audiobooks as podcasts helped <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/01/books/01podb.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0\" title=\"\">Scott Sigler become a self-publishing superstar</a>. Perhaps it's time for writers and performers on this side of the Atlantic to take note – and pick up a mic.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/podcasting\">Podcasting</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/internet\">Internet</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/digital-media\">Digital media</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dianeshipley\">Diane Shipley</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "US television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Podcasting") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Internet") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Digital media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Tue, 16 Apr 2013 16:42:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/16/marc-maron-comedy-podcast-tv") (dc:creator nil "Diane Shipley") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-16T17:39:09Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407307182") (media:keywords nil "Comedy, Television & radio, US television, Comedy, Television, Podcasting, Internet, Digital media, Media, Comedy, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366128783236/Marc-Maron-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Cassie Wright/WireImage") (media:description nil "Marc Maron's semi-autobiographical sitcom Maron premieres in May. Photograph: Cassie Wright/WireImage")))) ("Mad Men: season six, episode three" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/64839?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amad-men-season-six-episode-three%3A1895537&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Mad+Men+%28TV%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Paul+MacInnes&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+11%3A00&c8=1895537&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=Notes+from+the+break+room+%28Mad+Men%29&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Mad+Men%3A+season+six%2C+episode+three&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FMad+Men\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">In which Pete Campbell's marriage falls apart, we find out what beans mean and peek through a brothel wall at Don's younger self</p><p><em>SPOILER ALERT: This blog is for those who are watching season six of Mad Men. Don't read on if you haven't seen episodes one and two</em></p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/11/mad-men-season-six-episode-one-two\" title=\"\"><em>Catch up with Paul MacInnes's episode one and two blog here </em></a></p><p><strong>Episode three: The Collaborators</strong></p><h2>'It's just filled with profanity, marijuana smoking and simulated sexual acts … Oh, and a few songs' – Pete Campbell<br /></h2><p>The reign of Pete Campbell as the most unpleasant lothario in Cos Cob did not last long and neither was it edifying to watch. Determined to indulge himself as retribution for being made to live in the suburbs, Pete's first conquest was driven deeper into mental illness and his second ended up the victim of domestic violence. The ultimate consequence of this appears to be the immediate end of Pete's marriage. So at least something good came out of it.</p><p>Pete always seemed an unlikely type to inspire uncontrollable desire in women. His narrow-set features have something of the rodent about them, or perhaps a stoat. He's weedy and pale and seems shorn of any sense of romance (the spartan decor of his shag pad for, example, makes it look like something closer to a dungeon). This by the way, is without even touching upon the subject of his character which, when all's said and done, hardly works in his favour either.</p><p>Yet at the very beginning of this episode we get the distinct sense that Pete has beguiled not one but two neighbourhood women, while their husbands are stood in the next room. Those men, it has to be said, are in turn quite crassly chatting up Trudy Campbell. The conclusion one is reluctantly expected to draw from this juxtaposition is that Pete, by comparison, is a sophisticate. Topped off with his references to Hair, it seems the guy's a regular bohemian too.</p><p>So maybe Pete is simply taking advantage of a suburban desire for frisson. Or perhaps his neighbour, Brenda, just wanted access to a bolthole each time she came to Manhattan to shop. Either way, the next we see of her she's dressed like Jackie O and entirely willing to succumb to Pete's plodding advances.</p><p>Just a few days later, Brenda spills into the Campbells' sitting room, her nose bloodily busted and her husband's howl of \"You're Campbell's problem now\" trailing immediately behind. Pete plays the situation much as you'd expect: short of sympathy on the one hand and with cunning on the other. He suggests Brenda make her own way to a hotel in the middle of the night, before suddenly offering a lift when he realises his wife might drive her instead and find out the truth along the way.</p><p>That the truth does come out means the final scene in the Campbell household ends with Pete being instructed as to the scope of his micturatory privileges (he's not allowed to open his flies within 50 miles of his home). When she tells Pete she has decided to end their marriage, Trudy reveals a lot that we have really not seen before. She has proven cannier than we are often led to believe; she knew exactly what Pete's pad was intended for. She is also stern, clear and deliberate – less the subservient partner, more the daughter of a Vicks Chemical executive. Pete leaves the family home and dosses down in his office. </p><p>****</p><p>Away from the suburbs and back to the big city, where everyone's scrapping over condiments. There's an air of the ridiculous about proceedings, with people speaking in hushed tones of how \"beans brought in ketchup\" and asking themselves \"what can we do for ketchup?\" The reality for both <a href=\"http://madmen.wikia.com/wiki/Sterling_Cooper_Draper_Pryce\" title=\"\">SCDP</a> and <a href=\"http://madmen.wikia.com/wiki/Cutler_Gleason_and_Chaough\" title=\"\">Cutler, Gleason, and Chaough</a> is more serious, though, as Ken watches his ambitious plans being stifled and Ted Chaough plans to take advantage of a loose set of lips.</p><p>Ken's plan was simple: get beans to bring in ketchup and then, despite the expressed wishes of beans, run away with ketchup, the Coca-Cola of condiments. It was a simple plan and one entirely in keeping with the unsentimental nature of his business, but it was scotched by Don. Don felt that beans were owed some loyalty, that \"sometimes you gotta dance with the one that brung ya\". That hokey justification was entirely sentimental and entirely inconsistent with Don's subsequent, brilliant undermining of hideous Herb from Jaguar. Herb had brought Jaguar to SCDP and wanted them to change their strategy for his benefit and pitch it to his bosses too. Don did just as he was asked, but did it so egregiously that Herb's higher-ups refused to take the advice. An act of solidarity with Joan guided Don's actions, a personal act that may yet undermine his business interests.</p><p>There's nothing personal in the way that Ted leaps all over the news that Heinz ketchup might be up for grabs. Well there is, I guess, in that Ted sees SCDP as \"the enemy\". There's certainly no sentiment though as Peggy's accidental revelation of her late-night conversation with Stan, leads to the preparation of a brief the very next morning. Betraying information is how wars are won, Ted tells Peggy. \"He underestimated you.\"</p><p>****</p><p>Flashbacks are back back back. We know that Dick Whitman came from the school of hard knocks and, also, from the school of knocking shop. Here we get to see his time in the whorehouse. We are introduced to Ernestine the madam and Mack the rooster and Charlotte the prostitute in a scene that's eerily down home, all full of pleasantries and sweet swing music in the background. Later the tone changes starkly enough as Dick watches Mack having sex with his pregnant stepmother through a keyhole.</p><p>An elegant segue follows this scene as the camera pans past a sullen Dick, through the whorehouse wall, and out into the corridor of Don's apartment block. Don is there, shuffling towards his front door having allowed his priapism to take him to the verge of a disastrous encounter with Sylvia Rosen. He's just a gigolo, the old time song tells us, whose youth will pass away. (And what will they say of him then?) That Don's sex drive comes partly from a compulsion to demean his better self becomes clearer as time goes on.</p><p>****</p><p>As yet, Megan Draper has not a clue about her husband's infidelity and neither does she know he feels the pair are \"drifting apart\". She is, however, experiencing traumas of her own. An unplanned pregnancy in Hawaii is followed by a miscarriage and not only is Megan unable to share this event with anyone, it confirms in her another secret; her unwillingness to have children at all.</p><p>This is all worked out through a spontaneous confession to Sylvia in the washroom and, later, a dishonest conversation with Don. On both occasions, Megan's pain is coloured by her self-involvement. She assumes a sympathetic hearing from Sylvia, only to find that a shared Catholic upbringing resulted in very different moral codes. With Don, meanwhile, she jumps on an open-ended offer to have a conversation about children \"whenever you want\", to avoid the question altogether.</p><p>Don raises his eyebrows at this and we see that his willingness to accept Megan's indulgence of her own interests is limited. We also know, however, that Don is a hypocrite. He may think his desire to start another family is the normal, responsible thing, but he also feels free to ignore familial responsibilities. There is a generational difference between this couple, but they share a common selfishness.</p><h2>Notes</h2><p>We're only at episode three but already Bob Benson is making inroads. He's earned the trust of Pete, who allowed him to buy the most intimate of products for him. He's worked his obsequy on Herb with enough success to be granted the role of office tour guide. What next? A blowback from Stan?</p><p>We've not seen enough of Joan Holloway so far this season but she has been afforded one zinger of a line. In response to Herb's nauseating insistence that \"I know there's a part of you that wants to see me,\" she replies: \"I know there's a part of you that you haven't seen in years.\"</p><h2>Time stamps</h2><p>The <a href=\"http://www.clemson.edu/caah/history/FacultyPages/EdMoise/viet8.html\">Tet offensive</a> was one of the most notorious events in the Vietnam war, as the Viet Cong took advantage of a ceasefire (for the Vietnamese new year) to unleash brutal assaults on several south Vietnamese cities. These assaults were, in turn, crushed equally brutally by US and South Vietnamese forces. When this news is announced during this episode, Don and Sylvia pay no attention, too busy discussing the etiquette of dinner between adulterous couples.</p><p>The greatest conspiracy theory of the 20th century – who killed Kennedy? – was about to get a leg up as a Louisiana district attorney Jim Garrison <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Shl-F5qHN4U\">revealed to the American public</a> his belief that Lee Harvey Oswald had not acted alone.</p><h2>Culture club</h2><p>Hair: The American Tribal Love Rock Musical, to give it its full name, made its debut off-Broadway in 1967. It transferred to Broadway in the spring of 68 and slightly revised its bonkers premise for a broader audience. One of the changes involved turning the character of Claude from a space alien to a human. Its subsequent success may have lain partly in such revisions, but also in the fact it wasn't nearly as <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/theatre/2009/04/13/090413crth_theatre_als\">counter-cultural</a> as it thought it was.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/mad-men-tv-series\">Mad Men</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/paulmacinnes\">Paul MacInnes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/mad-men-season-six-episode-three" (20847 7008) old 28 nil nil ((title nil "Mad Men: season six, episode three") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/17/mad-men-season-six-episode-three") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/64839?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amad-men-season-six-episode-three%3A1895537&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Mad+Men+%28TV%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CHistorical+drama+%28TV+genre%2