But, man, this girl can also just be.\"</p><p>Day-Lewis, also an Oscar winner this year thanks to his role in Spielberg's Lincoln biopic, was described as \"a deep-sea creature who's unexpectedly approachable and thoroughly delightful company\" by the film's scriptwriter Tony Kushner. </p><p>\"The power and grace of Daniel's performances seem to emanate from something he's made contact with, deep within, intensely private and specific to his experience but also mysteriously universal,\" he continued.</p><p>The list is not ranked, but is divided into the categories Titans, Leaders, Pioneers, Icons and Artists. Neither Lawrence nor Spielberg (Artists both) have made it onto the Icon list. Day-Lewis shares that honour with Beyonce, Justin Timberlake and Kate Middleton.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/jennifer-lawrence\">Jennifer Lawrence</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/time-magazine\">Time magazine</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/danieldaylewis\">Daniel Day-Lewis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/stevenspielberg\">Steven Spielberg</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/jodie-foster\">Jodie Foster</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/bryan-cranston\">Bryan Cranston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/beyonce\">Beyoncé</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/justin-timberlake\">Justin Timberlake</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/girls\">Girls</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/breaking-bad\">Breaking Bad</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/henrybarnes\">Henry Barnes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Jennifer Lawrence") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Film") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Time magazine") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Daniel Day-Lewis") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Steven Spielberg") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Jodie Foster") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Bryan Cranston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/music")) "Beyoncé") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Justin Timberlake") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Girls") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Breaking Bad") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 17:54:05 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2013/apr/18/jennifer-lawrence-time-magazine") (dc:creator nil "Henry Barnes") (dc:subject nil "Film") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T17:54:05Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407461985") (media:keywords nil "Jennifer Lawrence, Film, Culture, Media, Time magazine, Daniel Day-Lewis, Steven Spielberg, Jodie Foster, Bryan Cranston, Beyoncé, Justin Timberlake, Girls, Breaking Bad") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Film/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306503324/Jennifer-Lawrence-and-Jod-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Jennifer Lawrence and Jodie Foster on set of The Beaver")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Film/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366306509837/Jennifer-Lawrence-and-Jod-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "'She can also just be' … Jennifer Lawrence and Jodie Foster with Anton Yelchin on set of The Beaver")))) ("Yemi Ajibade obituary" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91498?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ayemi-ajibade-obituary%3A1896039&ch=From+the+Guardian&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Stage%2CCulture%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media%2CTheatre&c6=Femi+Elufowoju+Jr&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+05%3A57&c8=1896039&c9=Article&c10=Obituary&c13=Other+lives+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Yemi+Ajibade+obituary&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FFrom+the+Guardian%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>When the BBC producer John Stockbridge was approached by the World Service in the 60s to create a drama for African listeners, he chose Yemi Ajibade, a promising young actor from west Africa with an established theatre career, for the lead role. The series was never made, but from then onwards Yemi, who has died aged 82, regularly featured on radio. His talent was spotted, too, by television producers and he appeared in series including Danger Man (1965), Dixon of Dock Green (1968), The Black Safari (1972) and The Fosters (1976).</p><p>Yemi's play Parcel Post (1976) explored the clash of traditional African virtues with the values of modern Britain. It was directed by Donald Howarth at the Royal Court in London and, during the theatre's 50th birthday celebrations in 2006, Howarth recalled that the play had a \"reconditioning\" effect on audiences. Among Yemi's other stage plays were Fingers Only (1982), Waiting for Hannibal (1986), Para Ginto (1995) – Peer Gynt transposed to African soil – and A Long Way From Home (1991).</p><p>Yemi was born in Otta, Nigeria, from a line of Yoruba kings. The foundations of his love for theatre and the arts were laid at Abeokuta grammar school. In the mid-1950s Yemi travelled to the UK intending to become a journalist, but read a book on Stanislavsky and thought: \"This is it.\" Yemi joined the Actors' Workshop in 1960 and the London School of Film Technique (now the London Film School) in 1966. Later, he took a master's degree at Royal Holloway, University of London.</p><p>In 1995 Jude Kelly, as artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse, invited Yemi to join the cast of Wole Soyinka's Beatification of Area Boy as part of the Africa 95 celebration. His final stage appearance was on the Olivier stage at the National theatre in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2007/aug/29/theatre1\" title=\"\">Thea Sharrock's 2007 production of Emperor Jones</a>.</p><p>Yemi inspired a younger generation of Nigerian writers and artists in the UK. I first met him in 1991 at Bush House for a BBC World Service radio drama recording. He became a firm source of encouragement and in subsequent years attended every production I produced or directed. During its 10th anniversary All African Stars Gala (2008) at Theatre Royal Stratford East, the British-African theatre company Tiata Fahodzi (which I founded) recognised his contribution to British theatre.</p><p>He is survived by his wife, the actor and poet Ebony White, and their two daughters, Adenrele and Mimi; another daughter, Marigold, from a previous relationship; and three sisters, Arinade Victoria, Layo and Janet.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/18/yemi-ajibade-obituary" (20848 9707) old 23 nil nil ((title nil "Yemi Ajibade obituary") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/18/yemi-ajibade-obituary") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91498?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ayemi-ajibade-obituary%3A1896039&ch=From+the+Guardian&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Stage%2CCulture%2CRadio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media%2CTheatre&c6=Femi+Elufowoju+Jr&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+05%3A57&c8=1896039&c9=Article&c10=Obituary&c13=Other+lives+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Yemi+Ajibade+obituary&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FFrom+the+Guardian%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>When the BBC producer John Stockbridge was approached by the World Service in the 60s to create a drama for African listeners, he chose Yemi Ajibade, a promising young actor from west Africa with an established theatre career, for the lead role. The series was never made, but from then onwards Yemi, who has died aged 82, regularly featured on radio. His talent was spotted, too, by television producers and he appeared in series including Danger Man (1965), Dixon of Dock Green (1968), The Black Safari (1972) and The Fosters (1976).</p><p>Yemi's play Parcel Post (1976) explored the clash of traditional African virtues with the values of modern Britain. It was directed by Donald Howarth at the Royal Court in London and, during the theatre's 50th birthday celebrations in 2006, Howarth recalled that the play had a \"reconditioning\" effect on audiences. Among Yemi's other stage plays were Fingers Only (1982), Waiting for Hannibal (1986), Para Ginto (1995) – Peer Gynt transposed to African soil – and A Long Way From Home (1991).</p><p>Yemi was born in Otta, Nigeria, from a line of Yoruba kings. The foundations of his love for theatre and the arts were laid at Abeokuta grammar school. In the mid-1950s Yemi travelled to the UK intending to become a journalist, but read a book on Stanislavsky and thought: \"This is it.\" Yemi joined the Actors' Workshop in 1960 and the London School of Film Technique (now the London Film School) in 1966. Later, he took a master's degree at Royal Holloway, University of London.</p><p>In 1995 Jude Kelly, as artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse, invited Yemi to join the cast of Wole Soyinka's Beatification of Area Boy as part of the Africa 95 celebration. His final stage appearance was on the Olivier stage at the National theatre in <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2007/aug/29/theatre1\" title=\"\">Thea Sharrock's 2007 production of Emperor Jones</a>.</p><p>Yemi inspired a younger generation of Nigerian writers and artists in the UK. I first met him in 1991 at Bush House for a BBC World Service radio drama recording. He became a firm source of encouragement and in subsequent years attended every production I produced or directed. During its 10th anniversary All African Stars Gala (2008) at Theatre Royal Stratford East, the British-African theatre company Tiata Fahodzi (which I founded) recognised his contribution to British theatre.</p><p>He is survived by his wife, the actor and poet Ebony White, and their two daughters, Adenrele and Mimi; another daughter, Marigold, from a previous relationship; and three sisters, Arinade Victoria, Layo and Janet.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage")) "Stage") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Obituaries") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 16:57:15 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2013/apr/18/yemi-ajibade-obituary") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "From the Guardian") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T16:57:15Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407454367") (media:keywords nil "Stage, Culture, Radio, Television & radio, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366299759060/Yemi-Ajibade-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Public Domain") (media:description nil "Yemi Ajibade's play Parcel Post was staged at the Royal Court, London, in 1976")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366299764853/Yemi-Ajibade-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Public Domain") (media:description nil "Yemi Ajibade's play Parcel Post was staged at the Royal Court, London, in 1976")))) ("Mrs Brown's Boys star: I brought Thatcher her tipple | Media Monkey" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/78320?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amrs-browns-boys-thatcher%3A1895768&ch=Media&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+industry+%28Media%29%2CMedia%2CComedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CCulture%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CMargaret+Thatcher%2CPolitics%2CUK+news&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Monkey&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+12%3A06&c8=1895768&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CNews&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Media+Monkey+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Mrs+Brown%27s+Boys+star%3A+I+brought+Thatcher+her+tipple&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2FTelevision+industry\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>Among all the acres of coverage of Margaret Thatcher's funeral, there is one small TV-related fact: Mrs Brown's Boys creator and star <strong>Brendan O'Carroll</strong> once served as the former prime minister's butler. It took place in 1984 during an EU leaders' summit at Dublin Castle, reports the Daily Express. \"The first thing Mrs Thatcher said to me when she got out of the helicopter was that she wanted an Irish whiskey. She said it was her first time in Ireland and she had always wanted to try one.\" The Irish comic added: \"I can remember being woken up one night by Mrs Thatcher's M15 security team, who told me that the prime minister wanted 'hot milk and pepper' in her apartment. I brought it down to her, and years later when RTE offered me a quizshow and asked what I should call it, I said Hot Milk and Pepper after Mrs T.\" </p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/margaretthatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/monkey\">Monkey</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/mediamonkeyblog/2013/apr/18/mrs-browns-boys-thatcher" (20847 54202) old 24 nil nil ((title nil "Mrs Brown's Boys star: I brought Thatcher her tipple | Media Monkey") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/mediamonkeyblog/2013/apr/18/mrs-browns-boys-thatcher") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/78320?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amrs-browns-boys-thatcher%3A1895768&ch=Media&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+industry+%28Media%29%2CMedia%2CComedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CCulture%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29%2CMargaret+Thatcher%2CPolitics%2CUK+news&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Monkey&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+12%3A06&c8=1895768&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CNews&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Media+Monkey+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Mrs+Brown%27s+Boys+star%3A+I+brought+Thatcher+her+tipple&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2FTelevision+industry\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>Among all the acres of coverage of Margaret Thatcher's funeral, there is one small TV-related fact: Mrs Brown's Boys creator and star <strong>Brendan O'Carroll</strong> once served as the former prime minister's butler. It took place in 1984 during an EU leaders' summit at Dublin Castle, reports the Daily Express. \"The first thing Mrs Thatcher said to me when she got out of the helicopter was that she wanted an Irish whiskey. She said it was her first time in Ireland and she had always wanted to try one.\" The Irish comic added: \"I can remember being woken up one night by Mrs Thatcher's M15 security team, who told me that the prime minister wanted 'hot milk and pepper' in her apartment. I brought it down to her, and years later when RTE offered me a quizshow and asked what I should call it, I said Hot Milk and Pepper after Mrs T.\" </p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/margaretthatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/monkey\">Monkey</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Comedy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Margaret Thatcher") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 11:06:34 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/mediamonkeyblog/2013/apr/18/mrs-browns-boys-thatcher") (dc:creator nil "Monkey") (dc:subject nil "Media") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T11:16:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407433043") (media:keywords nil "Television industry, Media, Comedy, Culture, Television, Comedy, Margaret Thatcher, Politics, UK news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366283060640/Mrs-Browns-Boys-Brendan-O-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Alan Peebles/BBC") (media:description nil "Mrs Brown's Boys: Brendan O'Carroll Photograph: Alan Peebles/BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366283069348/Mrs-Browns-Boys-Brendan-O-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Alan Peebles/BBC") (media:description nil "Mrs Brown's Boys: Brendan O'Carroll brought the Iron Lady the hard stuff. Photograph: Alan Peebles/BBC")))) ("The best adverts of the week: MTV, Wispa and Vodafone - video" "<p>Watch a review of the best new TV commercials from around the world</p><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jason-stone\">Jason Stone</a></div><br/><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/video/2013/apr/18/mtv-wispa-hot-chocolate-vodafone-video" (20847 38808) old 25 nil nil ((title nil "The best adverts of the week: MTV, Wispa and Vodafone - video") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/video/2013/apr/18/mtv-wispa-hot-chocolate-vodafone-video") (description nil "<p>Watch a review of the best new TV commercials from around the world</p><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/jason-stone\">Jason Stone</a></div><br/><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Advertising") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Editorial") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 06:50:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/video/2013/apr/18/mtv-wispa-hot-chocolate-vodafone-video") (dc:creator nil "Jason Stone") (dc:subject nil "Media") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T10:05:25Z") (dc:type nil "Video") (dc:identifier nil "407359478") (media:keywords nil "Advertising, Media, Television, Television & radio, UK news, United States") (media:group nil (media:content ((fileSize . "34214825") (type . "video/mp4") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/truemainwebsite/2013/4/17mainwebsite/2013/4/17/130417AdBreakMTVWispa-16x9.mp4"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "144791986") (type . "video/mp4:720") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/4/17/130417AdBreakMTVWispa-720.mp4"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "36329596") (type . "video/3gpp:small") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/4/17/130417AdBreakMTVWispa_3gpSml16x9.3gp"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "67870344") (type . "video/3gpp:large") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/4/17/130417AdBreakMTVWispa_3gpLg16x9.3gp"))) (media:content ((type . "video/m3u8") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/4/17/130417AdBreakMTVWispa/130417AdBreakMTVWispa.m3u8")))) (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366196867762/MTV-Movie-awards-ad-Chann-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Screengrab") (media:description nil "MTV Movie awards ad: Channing Tatum and Rebel Wilson")))) ("Britain's Youngest Head Chef" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/1967?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abritains-youngest-head-chef-tv-review%3A1895410&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Tim+Dowling&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+07%3A00&c8=1895410&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Britain%27s+Youngest+Head+Chef%3B+Syria%3A+Across+the+Lines+%E2%80%93+TV+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Despite the intended story arc, the protagonist of Britain's Youngest Head Chef appeared to be the only one showing any wisdom</p><p>Luke Thomas is 18, but looks younger. He's also <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zz2\" title=\"Britains Youngest Top Chef \"><strong>Britain's Youngest Head Chef </strong></a>(BBC3), with a string of awards and posh work experience placements behind him. Now he's also chef patron of a restaurant in a boutique country hotel labouring&nbsp;under the name of Sanctum on the Green.</p><p>Its owner, self-styled \"rock'n'roll hotelier\" Mark Fuller, was so impressed by Luke he went into business with him without even tasting his food first. Why would he do that? \"I would be lying if I said that I didn't think it would be good for the business and a great PR angle,\" said Fuller. Ah. Luke's agent, Borra Garson, also took him on without trying the food. \"I never felt cynical about it,\" she said. Feeling cynical, it seems, was for the rest of us.</p><p>Actually, the one thing that was never in doubt in this diverting documentary was Luke's ability to cook. But there was calculation behind the narrative's trajectory: the boy has bitten off more than he can chew; the pressure is too much for him; he's only 18 after all.</p><p>The result was the sort of car crash you suspect has been engineered for the insurance. Fuller took Luke to London to try his hand at VIP catering for the Wireless festival – the bread-and-butter business that enables Fuller to maintain a nine-room boutique hotel – then complained that Luke needed to spend more time in the restaurant's kitchen.</p><p>Throughout the programme Fuller had much to say about Luke's relative immaturity, his inflated expectations, his love of publicity and his business inexperience. It was hard not to think:&nbsp;but you're the one who hired him and&nbsp;you didn't even taste the food&nbsp;first.</p><p>The only person who seemed unable to follow the script was Luke, whose self-belief never faltered. Once you got over the fact that he sounded like a kid reading a script meant for Marco Pierre White, Luke came across as driven, appealingly arrogant and right about everything.</p><p>His criticisms of the restaurant's decor were both wildly impolitic and spot on. \"I can't stand these tables,\" he said, looking at them as if they alone stood between him and his first Michelin star. \"There's a mark on the wall, there's a big cobweb up there, the bulbs are too bright, the side plates don't look right, that glass isn't polished.\"</p><p>This was ostensibly a documentary about a talented but overambitious young lad who would learn from his mistakes before he jeopardised a bright future. But I'm afraid I came away thinking that all the difficulties at Sanctum on the Green could have been overcome more quickly if everybody&nbsp;had just shut up and listened to Luke.</p><p>We have had documentaries examining the roots of the present Syrian conflict, but the most pressing question about the war is not \"How did it start?\" but \"Why isn't it over?\"</p><p><a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/dispatches/episode-guide/series-126/episode-1\" title=\"Syria: Across The Lines\"><strong>Syria: Across the Lines</strong></a> (Channel&nbsp;4) examined the deadly stalemate in microcosm. Film-maker Olly Lambert spend five dangerous weeks in the Orontes river valley, where until recently Alawites and Sunnis lived in peaceful coexistence. Now they shoot at each other across the river, while crops rot in no man's land.</p><p>Ahmad defected from the police force to the Free Syrian Army and grew a beard to mark the change. \"He's just grown it for appearances,\" said his mum. \"It's not really him.\"</p><p>At the rebel HQ in the village of Kansafra, they have a portrait of Assad on the floor, so they can step on it every time they go in or out. Across the river, the Assad&nbsp;portraits are hung on the wall, but other differences are not immediately apparent.</p><p>The front line is a long way from the political and ideological forces driving the conflict. As one rebel leader said dismissively of a totally unobserved ceasefire: \"These decisions are made by people who live abroad.\"</p><p>On the government-held side of the valley, soldiers believe the rebels have been infiltrated by foreign extremists, but rebel and Sunni are still used interchangeably – as, on the other side, are Alawite and regime. Rebels openly vowed to inflict casualties on Alawite civilians. A government soldier said, \"You either win, or you die.\"</p><p>When the bearded Ahmad was injured by bombs from fighter jets, his mother promised to drink Assad's blood. Meanwhile, people keep dying either side of the Orontes river and  there is no end in sight.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/series/watchthis\" title=\"\">• Watch this: TV highlights</a></p><p><a href=\"http://tvlistings.guardian.co.uk/default.aspx\" title=\"\">• Full TV listings</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/timdowling\">Tim Dowling</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/britains-youngest-head-chef-tv-review" (20847 35816) old 26 nil nil ((title nil "Britain's Youngest Head Chef") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/britains-youngest-head-chef-tv-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/1967?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abritains-youngest-head-chef-tv-review%3A1895410&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Tim+Dowling&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+07%3A00&c8=1895410&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Britain%27s+Youngest+Head+Chef%3B+Syria%3A+Across+the+Lines+%E2%80%93+TV+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height