) (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T23:05:10Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407388906") (media:keywords nil "Margaret Thatcher, Politics, Television, Comedy, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/17/1366216527112/Margaret-Thatcher-Spittin-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "ITV/Rex Features") (media:description nil "One of Spitting Image's Margaret Thatcher puppets: 'As she became more strident, the puppet became more manic and manly.' Photograph: ITV/Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/17/1366216533675/Margaret-Thatcher-Spittin-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "ITV/Rex Features") (media:description nil "One of Spitting Image's Margaret Thatcher puppets: 'As she became more strident, the puppet became more manic and manly.' Photograph: ITV/Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "573") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/17/1366216738179/Margaret-Thatcher-with-st-001.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "John Lawrence Jones/Spitting Image") (media:description nil "'We had a great deal of fun with the Leaderine.' Photograph: John Lawrence Jones/Spitting Image")))) ("My Animals and Other Family by Clare Balding – review" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/42578?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amy-animals-family-clare-balding%3A1894796&ch=Books&c3=Guardian&c4=Autobiography+and+memoir+%28books+genre%29%2CBiography+%28Books+genre%29%2CBooks%2CCulture%2CClare+Balding%2CSport+and+leisure+%28Books+genre%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTV&c6=Victoria+Segal&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A59&c8=1894796&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=My+Animals+and+Other+Family+by+Clare+Balding+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FAutobiography+and+memoir\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Balding's autobiography contains irresistible insights into a certain kind of English family</p><p>Were post-Olympics Britain to vote for a head girl, it would be a fair bet that the honour would fall to Clare Balding. If it's not shocking to learn from the&nbsp;first volume of her endearing autobiography that she has form as a boarding school prefect, there are also little surprises embedded in the sports broadcaster's account of her early life. The daughter of a racehorse trainer, she measures out her life in ponies, boxers and lurchers, but even those who find the sporting life a distasteful mulch of dog slaver, moult and mucking out will find it hard to resist stories of the young Balding bowling into her house in filthy jodhpurs to find&nbsp;the Queen eating breakfast, or the&nbsp;<em>Mean Girls</em> atmosphere of boarding school pranks. Balding's love of animals is warmly expressed, a striking contrast to her rancour-free insights into a certain kind of English family, one who considered a brisk wave to be a public display of affection and who might easily forget to pick up their daughter for her first school holiday. As this biography underlines, however, she has turned out rather well.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/autobiography-and-memoir\">Autobiography and memoir</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/biography\">Biography</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/clare-balding\">Clare Balding</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/sportandleisure\">Sport and leisure</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/victoriasegal\">Victoria Segal</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/19/my-animals-family-clare-balding" (20849 30677) old 13 nil nil ((title nil "My Animals and Other Family by Clare Balding – review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/19/my-animals-family-clare-balding") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/42578?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amy-animals-family-clare-balding%3A1894796&ch=Books&c3=Guardian&c4=Autobiography+and+memoir+%28books+genre%29%2CBiography+%28Books+genre%29%2CBooks%2CCulture%2CClare+Balding%2CSport+and+leisure+%28Books+genre%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTV&c6=Victoria+Segal&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A59&c8=1894796&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=My+Animals+and+Other+Family+by+Clare+Balding+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FAutobiography+and+memoir\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Balding's autobiography contains irresistible insights into a certain kind of English family</p><p>Were post-Olympics Britain to vote for a head girl, it would be a fair bet that the honour would fall to Clare Balding. If it's not shocking to learn from the&nbsp;first volume of her endearing autobiography that she has form as a boarding school prefect, there are also little surprises embedded in the sports broadcaster's account of her early life. The daughter of a racehorse trainer, she measures out her life in ponies, boxers and lurchers, but even those who find the sporting life a distasteful mulch of dog slaver, moult and mucking out will find it hard to resist stories of the young Balding bowling into her house in filthy jodhpurs to find&nbsp;the Queen eating breakfast, or the&nbsp;<em>Mean Girls</em> atmosphere of boarding school pranks. Balding's love of animals is warmly expressed, a striking contrast to her rancour-free insights into a certain kind of English family, one who considered a brisk wave to be a public display of affection and who might easily forget to pick up their daughter for her first school holiday. As this biography underlines, however, she has turned out rather well.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/autobiography-and-memoir\">Autobiography and memoir</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/biography\">Biography</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/clare-balding\">Clare Balding</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/sportandleisure\">Sport and leisure</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/victoriasegal\">Victoria Segal</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Autobiography and memoir") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Biography") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Books") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Clare Balding") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Sport and leisure") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 16:59:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/19/my-animals-family-clare-balding") (dc:creator nil "Victoria Segal") (dc:subject nil "Books") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T16:59:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407302971") (media:keywords nil "Autobiography and memoir, Biography, Books, Culture, Clare Balding, Sport and leisure") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2013/4/16/1366126987104/1527354c-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Julian Andrews / Rex Features/Julian Andrews / Rex Features") (media:description nil "Good sport … TV presenter and journalist Clare Balding. Photograph: Julian Andrews / Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2013/4/16/1366126993018/1527354c-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Julian Andrews / Rex Features/Julian Andrews / Rex Features") (media:description nil "Sporting … TV presenter and journalist Clare Balding. Photograph: Julian Andrews/ Rex Features")))) ("A reality TV Mars landing may be silly, but at least it's on the right track | Steven Poole" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/529?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areality-tv-mars-landing%3A1896475&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Netherlands+%28News%29%2CNasa%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CSpace+%28Science%29%2CScience%2CMars+%28Science%29%2CReality+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Steven+Poole&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A35&c8=1896475&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=A+reality+TV+Mars+landing+may+be+silly%2C+but+at+least+it%27s+on+the+right+track&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Let's have a show in which top materials-science researchers vie to invent a more efficient kind of solar cell</p><p>Resurgent pop colossus David Bowie can look forward to even more royalties from Life on Mars? if <a href=\"http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/04/18/one_way_mars_one_big_brother/\" title=\"\">a Dutch project called Mars One goes according to plan</a>. This week it announced it would start taking video applications from members of the public who want to go on a one-way trip to Mars in 2023 for a reality TV show. Among the hopefuls might be British people forced out of their council flats by the \"bedroom tax\".</p><p></p><p>On Mars, the four initial residents –&nbsp;having been voted winners by the viewers from a pool of 40 – will get a roomy 50 sq m apartment each. Going off-planet is certainly one radical solution to the housing crisis. Strap a few hundred Barratt Homes developers onto a giant rocket as well and the red planet is your oyster.</p><p></p><p>It's an expensive project –&nbsp;the organisers hope to raise the £4bn cost by selling media rights – and a technically ambitious one, too. Mars One plans first to send a rover to choose a location, and then blast over food, generators, life-support and other gear – using vehicles from the private company SpaceX – before the humans arrive. But Nasa, who are the experts to date at sending stuff far away from Earth, have lost a number of craft they've sent to Mars. And what they've been able to land on the planet are a few adorable trundling robots rather than a self-supporting village for wannabe space celebrities.</p><p></p><p>Let's assume, though, that the contestants get there (after eight years of rigorous training), and can breathe and eat. They'll suffer constant video surveillance in a hostile environment, but then so do millions of Londoners. But what if they fall ill? Even if the producers make sure one of the contestants is a doctor, a single doctor can't be a specialist in everything. So it would probably be better if they were all doctors. Then the show could be sold as a kind of real-life Grey's Anatomy in space, with the inevitable low-gravity loving.</p><p>Cultural puritans might denounce the whole idea as a perverse extreme of reality TV, which in its Big Brother incarnation – a format also invented by the Dutch – was always designed primarily as a form of psychological torture for our sadistic viewing pleasure. In Mars One, the contestants are expected to die on set, which is a fate arguably even worse than having Simon Cowell touch you (more contestants will be sent out every two years, with the aim of establishing a self-sustaining community, but there will be no trips home).</p><p></p><p>Yet there still seems something heroic about this silly project. The Earth will be burned to a crisp and swallowed up by a bloated red-giant Sun in about 7bn years. If we haven't got used to colonising other planets and eventually other star systems by then, that will be the end of the human race.</p><p></p><p>If governments are no longer willing to fund such inspirational <em>grands projets</em>, we should be happy that other entities think they can raise the money instead, even if those entities are TV producers (the idea of privatised game-show space tourism would surely have tickled Lady Thatcher). And for those who think interplanetary exploration is just nonsense for space nerds, the same lessons could surely be applied closer to home.</p><p></p><p>Let's have a reality-TV contest in which top materials-science researchers vie to invent a more efficient kind of solar cell in order to combat global warming, while also having to rehearse and perform an entire postmodern circus in skimpy costumes. Or, since 61% of the UK public now believe that utilities are better run in public hands, we could make a reality-TV show out of economists and other wonks trying desperately to renationalise the electricity supply. I for one am quite optimistic about the viewing figures for Britain's Got Current.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/netherlands\">Netherlands</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/nasa\">Nasa</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/space\">Space</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/mars\">Mars</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/reality-tv\">Reality TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stevenpoole\">Steven Poole</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/reality-tv-mars-landing" (20849 29273) old 3 nil nil ((title nil "A reality TV Mars landing may be silly, but at least it's on the right track | Steven Poole") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/reality-tv-mars-landing") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/529?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areality-tv-mars-landing%3A1896475&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.